{"title_page": "2020 Sri Lankan parliamentary election", "text_new": "{{use dmy dates |date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name = 16th Sri Lankan parliamentary election\n| country = Sri Lanka\n| type = parliamentary\n| ongoing = yes\n| previous_election = 2015 Sri Lankan parliamentary election\n| previous_year = 2015\n| previous_mps= \n| next_election =\n| next_year =\n| next_mps= \n| seats_for_election = All 225 seats to the [[Parliament of Sri Lanka]] <br /> 113 seats are needed for a majority\n| election_date = TBD <br /><small>[[16th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]</small>\n| turnout =\n\n<!--     United National Party      -->\n| image1 = [[File:Ranil_Wickremesinghe.jpg|120px]]\n| leader1 = [[Ranil Wickramasinghe]]\n| leader_since1 = 1994\n| party1 = United National Party\n| leaders_seat1 = [[Colombo Electoral District|Colombo District]]\n| last_election1 = 106{{Efn|Represents seats won by the now defunct [[United National Front for Good Governance]] (UNFGG) at the [[2015 Sri Lankan parliamentary election|2015 parliamentary election]].}}\n| seats_needed1 = 7\n| states_carried1 = \n| seats1 = \n| seat_change1 = \n| popular_vote1 = \n| percentage1 = \n| swing1 =\n\n<!--     Sri Lanka People's Freedom Alliance      -->\n| image2 = [[File:Mahinda Rajapaksa 2006.jpg|120px]]\n| leader2 = [[Mahinda Rajapaksa]]\n| leader_since2 = 2019\n| party2 = Sri Lanka People's Freedom Alliance\n| leaders_seat2 = [[Kurunegala Electoral District|Kurunegala District]]\n| last_election2 = 95{{Efn|Represents seats won by the now defunct [[United People's Freedom Alliance]] (UPFA) at the [[2015 Sri Lankan parliamentary election|2015 parliamentary election]].}}\n| seats_needed2 = 18\n| states_carried2 = \n| seats2 = \n| seat_change2 = \n| popular_vote2 = \n| percentage2 = \n| swing2 =\n\n<!--    Samagi Jana Balawegaya       -->\n| image3 = [[File:Sajith Premadasa.jpg|120px]]\n| leader3 = [[Sajith Premadasa]]\n| leader_since3 = 2020\n| color3 = 25442D\n| party3 = [[Samagi Jana Balawegaya]]\n| leaders_seat3 = [[Colombo Electoral District|Colombo District]]\n| last_election3 = New Party\n| seats_needed3 = 113\n| states_carried3 = \n| seats3 = \n| seat_change3 = \n| popular_vote3 = \n| percentage3 = \n| swing3 =\n\n<!--       Tamil National Alliance     -->\n| image4 = [[File:R. Sampanthan.jpg|120px]]\n| leader4 = [[R. Sampanthan]]\n| leader_since4 = 2001\n| party4 = Tamil National Alliance\n| leaders_seat4 = [[Trincomalee Electoral District|Trincomalee District]]\n| last_election4 = 16\n| seats_needed4 = 97\n| states_carried4 =\n| seats4 = \n| seat_change4 = \n| popular_vote4 = \n| percentage4 = \n| swing4 =\n\n<!--      Janatha Vimukthi Peramuna     -->\n| image5 = [[File:AnuraKumara.jpg|130px]]\n| leader5 = [[Anura Kumara Dissanayaka]]\n| leader_since5 = 2019\n| party5 =  National People's Power\n| color5 = 9F005D\n| leaders_seat5 = [[Colombo Electoral District|Colombo District]]\n| last_election5 = 6\n| seats_needed5 = 107\n| states_carried5 = \n| seats5 = \n| seat_change5 = \n| popular_vote5 = \n| percentage5 = \n| swing5 =\n\n| map_image          = \n| map_size           = 250px\n| map_caption        = \n| title              = [[Prime Minister of Sri Lanka|Prime Minister]]\n| posttitle          = [[Prime Minister of Sri Lanka|Prime Minister]]-designate\n| before_election    = [[Mahinda Rajapaksa]] \n| after_election     = \n| before_party       = [[United People's Freedom Alliance]]\n| after_party        = \n}}\n'''Parliamentary elections in Sri Lanka''' are scheduled to be held on 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/sri-lankan-parliament-dissolved-elections-set-april-200302193858515.html|title=Sri Lankan parliament dissolved; elections set for April|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2018, the date was briefly moved forward by more than a year to 5 January 2019 due to President [[Maithripala Sirisena]] dissolving parliament during a [[2018 Sri Lankan constitutional crisis|constitutional crisis]] and calling for a snap election.<ref name=\"parliamentdissolved\">{{cite news |last1=Bastians |first1=Dharisha |last2=Goel |first2=Vindu |title=Sri Lanka President Dissolves Parliament Amid Power Struggle |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/11/09/world/asia/sri-lanka-dissolves-parliament.html |accessdate=26 November 2018 |work=New York Times |date=9 November 2018 }}</ref> The Supreme Court later suspended the dissolution and ordered a halt to the snap election, effectively moving the election's date back to 2020.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sri Lanka Supreme Court overturns dissolution of parliament |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/11/sri-lanka-supreme-court-overturns-dissolution-parliament-181113125340789.html |accessdate=26 November 2018 |agency=Al Jazeera and news agencies |date=13 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, Election Commissioner [[Mahinda Deshapriya]] revealed that the election will be postponed indefinitely until further notice due to the coronavirus pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newsin.asia/sri-lankas-general-election-postponed/|title=Sri Lanka\u2019s General Election postponed till country is freed from COVID-19|date=2020-03-19|website=NewsIn.Asia|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.asiantribune.com/node/93497|title=Sri Lanka\u2019s General Election postponed: Until the polls Country comes under Election Commission {{!}} Asian Tribune|website=www.asiantribune.com|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> Sri Lankan government initially insisted that scheduled forthcoming the election would proceed as planned on 25 April despite the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Sri Lanka|coronavirus pandemic in the country]], and the authorities banned election rallies and meetings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://colombogazette.com/2020/03/15/president-tells-saarc-leaders-april-election-will-go-ahead/|title=President tells SAARC leaders April election will go ahead|last=admin|date=2020-03-15|website=Colombo Gazette|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> During the video conference with SAARC leaders, Sri Lankan President Gotabaya Rajapaksa initially confirmed that the parliamentary elections would be held as scheduled.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://menafn.com/1099857379/Sri-Lanka-President-tells-SAARC-leaders-April-election-will-go-ahead|title=Sri Lanka- President tells SAARC leaders April election will go ahead|last=MENAFN|website=menafn.com|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\n{{update section|date=February 2020|reason=events in 2019}}\n;2018\n* 9 November 2018 - President Maithripala Sirisena dissolves parliament and calls general elections to be held on January 5, 2019.<ref>https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-46156303</ref>\n* 13 December 2018 - The Supreme Court of Sri Lanka ruled unanimously that President Maithripala Sirisena's order to dissolve Parliament and hold new elections was unconstitutional.<ref>https://news.yahoo.com/sri-lanka-court-verdict-expected-parliaments-dissolution-090205031.html</ref>\n* 16 December 2018 - Ranil Wickramasinghe was sworn back as Prime Minister after the Supreme Court ruled that Mahinda Rajapaksa can not act as Prime Minister.<ref>https://www.tamilguardian.com/content/ranil-sworn-back-prime-minister</ref><ref>https://news.yahoo.com/sri-lanka-court-denies-rajapakse-authority-act-pm-105810542.html</ref>\n;2020\n* 30 January 2020 - [[United National Party]] working committee approves [[Leader of Opposition]] [[Sajith Premadasa]] as its Prime Minister candidate.<ref>http://www.colombopage.com/archive_20A/Jan30_1580399088CH.php</ref>\n* 10 February 2020 - Leader of the opposition [[Sajith Premadasa]] forms a new alliance called [[Samagi Jana Balawegaya]].<ref>https://english.theleader.lk/news/654-sajith-s-alliance-to-be-named-samagi-jana-balawegaya-with-the-heart-as-its-symbol</ref>\n* 17 February 2020 - Sri Lanka People's Freedom Alliance registered under the leadership of [[Mahinda Rajapaksa]] and [[Maithripala Sirisena]] named as chairperson.<ref>http://www.adaderana.lk/news/60849/slpp-and-slfp-to-contest-general-election-under-new-alliance-with-mahinda-as-leader</ref>\n* 3 March 2020- President dissolved Parliament, elections on April 25 2020 and nominations end March 18th.<ref>https://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/sri-lankan-parliament-dissolved-elections-on-april-25/story-qkVWPKjcJAQDX2E75P40kL.html</ref>\n* 13 March 2020 - Election Commission postpone the elections without announcing a new date due to COVID -19 pandamic.<ref>http://www.adaderana.lk/news/61545/sri-lankas-general-election-postponed</ref>\n* 3 April 2020 - Elections Commission write to the president asking him to see advise for a new date or make an alternative since they are unable to hold the elections as per presidents gazzate.<ref>http://constitutionnet.org/news/sri-lankan-election-commission-asks-president-seek-court-opinion-parliamentary-election-delay</ref>\n* 9 April 2020 - President's Secretary PB Jayasundara response to the commission that president will not get any advice from the courts on the elections, and it is the commissions' responsibility to hold the elections, warning of Constitutional Crisis.<ref>https://www.lankanewsweb.net/66-special-news/59902-Presidents-Secretary-responds-to-Election-Commission-on-the-warning-of-Constitutional-Crisis</ref>\n\n==Background==\nDuring the [[2018 Sri Lankan constitutional crisis|constitutional crisis]] in 2018, Sirisena dissolved parliament and ordered a snap election after his nominee for Prime Minister, Mahinda Rajapaksa, failed to gain a majority in Parliament to back his nomination.<ref name=\"parliamentdissolved\" />\n\nHowever, after the constitutionality of the dissolution was challenged before Sri Lanka's [[Supreme Court of Sri Lanka|Supreme Court]], the dissolution was suspended, and the snap election was put on hold while the court case was ongoing. On 13 December 2018, the Supreme Court ruled the dissolution of the parliament unconstitutional, moving the election back to its original date.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rasheed |first1=Zaheena |last2=Kuruwita |first2=Rathindra |title=Sri Lanka's Supreme Court overturns sacking of parliament |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/12/sri-lanka-supreme-court-overturns-sacking-parliament-181213113720319.html |accessdate=14 December 2018 |agency=Al Jazeera |date=13 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==COVID -19==\nOn March 19, 2020, Sri Lanka reported an increase in COVID-19 pandemic, but the government went ahead with the nominations until March 18, 2020, to close nominations to the elections. <ref>http://www.colombopage.com/archive_20A/Mar19_1584592211CH.php</ref>On March 19 soon after the nominations ended, the elections commission with its powers postpone the elections.<ref>http://www.adaderana.lk/news/61545/sri-lankas-general-election-postponed</ref>\n\n==Electoral system==\n196 MPs were elected from 22 multi-member [[Electoral districts in Sri Lanka|electoral districts]] using the [[D'Hondt method]] with an [[open list]], a [[proportional representation]] system.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Blanc|first1=Jarrett|last2=Hylland|first2=Aanund|last3=Vollan|first3=Kare|title=State Structure and Electoral Systems in Post-Conflict Situations|date=2006|publisher=[[International Foundation for Electoral Systems]]|isbn=1-931459-17-7|page=106|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1EXgwebG5oEC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Report of the Post-Election Assessment of Sri Lanka Mission: November 28 \u2013 December 2, 2000|url=https://www.ndi.org/files/1198_lk_postelect122000.pdf|publisher=[[National Democratic Institute for International Affairs]]|page=10|date=28 December 2000}}</ref> The remaining 29 seats were allocated to contesting [[List of political parties in Sri Lanka|parties]] and [[Independent politician|independent]] groups in proportion to their share of the national vote.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Thilakarathne|first1=N. M. C.|editor1-last=Brian|editor1-first=Rob|title=Parliamentary Libraries and Information Services of Asia and the Pacific: Papers prepared for the 62nd IFLA Conference Beijing, China August 25\u201331, 1996|date=1997|publisher=Walter de Gruyte|isbn=3-11-094763-3|page=87|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rlohAAAAQBAJ|chapter=Parliament Library of Sri Lanka}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sri Lanka: Parliament|url=http://www.ipu.org/parline/reports/2295.htm|publisher=[[Inter-Parliamentary Union]]}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Url|1=parliament.lk|2=Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n* {{Url|1=slelections.gov.lk|2=Department of Elections, Sri Lanka}}\n<references group=\"lower-alpha\" />\n\n{{Sri Lankan elections}}\n\n[[Category:Future elections in Asia|Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Parliamentary elections in Sri Lanka]]\n", "text_old": "{{use dmy dates |date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name = 16th Sri Lankan parliamentary election\n| country = Sri Lanka\n| type = parliamentary\n| ongoing = yes\n| previous_election = 2015 Sri Lankan parliamentary election\n| previous_year = 2015\n| previous_mps= \n| next_election =\n| next_year =\n| next_mps= \n| seats_for_election = All 225 seats to the [[Parliament of Sri Lanka]] <br /> 113 seats are needed for a majority\n| election_date = TBD <br /><small>[[16th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]</small>\n| turnout =\n\n<!--     United National Party      -->\n| image1 = [[File:Ranil_Wickremesinghe.jpg|120px]]\n| leader1 = [[Ranil Wickramasinghe]]\n| leader_since1 = 1994\n| party1 = United National Party\n| leaders_seat1 = [[Colombo Electoral District|Colombo District]]\n| last_election1 = 106{{Efn|Represents seats won by the now defunct [[United National Front for Good Governance]] (UNFGG) at the [[2015 Sri Lankan parliamentary election|2015 parliamentary election]].}}\n| seats_needed1 = 7\n| states_carried1 = \n| seats1 = \n| seat_change1 = \n| popular_vote1 = \n| percentage1 = \n| swing1 =\n\n<!--     Sri Lanka People's Freedom 