ccess-date=2020-03-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.asiantribune.com/node/93497|title=Sri Lanka\u2019s General Election postponed: Until the polls Country comes under Election Commission {{!}} Asian Tribune|website=www.asiantribune.com|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> Sri Lankan government initially insisted that scheduled forthcoming the election would proceed as planned on 25 April despite the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Sri Lanka|coronavirus pandemic in the country]], and the authorities banned election rallies and meetings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://colombogazette.com/2020/03/15/president-tells-saarc-leaders-april-election-will-go-ahead/|title=President tells SAARC leaders April election will go ahead|last=admin|date=2020-03-15|website=Colombo Gazette|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> During the video conference with SAARC leaders, Sri Lankan President Gotabaya Rajapaksa initially confirmed that the parliamentary elections would be held as scheduled.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://menafn.com/1099857379/Sri-Lanka-President-tells-SAARC-leaders-April-election-will-go-ahead|title=Sri Lanka- President tells SAARC leaders April election will go ahead|last=MENAFN|website=menafn.com|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\n{{update section|date=February 2020|reason=events in 2019}}\n;2018\n* 9 November 2018 - President Maithripala Sirisena dissolves parliament and calls general elections to be held on January 5, 2019.<ref>https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-46156303</ref>\n* 13 December 2018 - The Supreme Court of Sri Lanka ruled unanimously that President Maithripala Sirisena's order to dissolve Parliament and hold new elections was unconstitutional.<ref>https://news.yahoo.com/sri-lanka-court-verdict-expected-parliaments-dissolution-090205031.html</ref>\n* 16 December 2018 - Ranil Wickramasinghe was sworn back as Prime Minister after the Supreme Court ruled that Mahinda Rajapaksa can not act as Prime Minister.<ref>https://www.tamilguardian.com/content/ranil-sworn-back-prime-minister</ref><ref>https://news.yahoo.com/sri-lanka-court-denies-rajapakse-authority-act-pm-105810542.html</ref>\n;2020\n* 30 January 2020 - [[United National Party]] working committee approves [[Leader of Opposition]] [[Sajith Premadasa]] as its Prime Minister candidate.<ref>http://www.colombopage.com/archive_20A/Jan30_1580399088CH.php</ref>\n* 10 February 2020 - Leader of the opposition [[Sajith Premadasa]] forms a new alliance called [[Samagi Jana Balawegaya]].<ref>https://english.theleader.lk/news/654-sajith-s-alliance-to-be-named-samagi-jana-balawegaya-with-the-heart-as-its-symbol</ref>\n* 17 February 2020 - Sri Lanka People's Freedom Alliance registered under the leadership of [[Mahinda Rajapaksa]] and [[Maithripala Sirisena]] named as chairperson.<ref>http://www.adaderana.lk/news/60849/slpp-and-slfp-to-contest-general-election-under-new-alliance-with-mahinda-as-leader</ref>\n* 3 March 2020- President dissolved Parliament, elections on April 25 2020 and nominations end March 18th.<ref>https://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/sri-lankan-parliament-dissolved-elections-on-april-25/story-qkVWPKjcJAQDX2E75P40kL.html</ref>\n* 13 March 2020 - Election Commission postpone the elections without announcing a new date due to COVID -19 pandamic.<ref>http://www.adaderana.lk/news/61545/sri-lankas-general-election-postponed</ref>\n* 3 April 2020 - Elections Commission write to the president asking him to see advise for a new date or make an alternative since they are unable to hold the elections as per presidents gazzate.<ref>http://constitutionnet.org/news/sri-lankan-election-commission-asks-president-seek-court-opinion-parliamentary-election-delay</ref>\n* 9 April 2020 - President's Secretary PB Jayasundara response to the commission that president will not get any advice from the courts on the elections, and its the commissions' responsibility to hold the elections, warning of Constitutional Crisis.<ref>https://www.lankanewsweb.net/66-special-news/59902-Presidents-Secretary-responds-to-Election-Commission-on-the-warning-of-Constitutional-Crisis</ref>\n==Background==\nDuring the [[2018 Sri Lankan constitutional crisis|constitutional crisis]] in 2018, Sirisena dissolved parliament and ordered a snap election after his nominee for Prime Minister, Mahinda Rajapaksa, failed to gain a majority in Parliament to back his nomination.<ref name=\"parliamentdissolved\" />\n\nHowever, after the constitutionality of the dissolution was challenged before Sri Lanka's [[Supreme Court of Sri Lanka|Supreme Court]], the dissolution was suspended, and the snap election was put on hold while the court case was ongoing. On 13 December 2018, the Supreme Court ruled the dissolution of the parliament unconstitutional, moving the election back to its original date.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rasheed |first1=Zaheena |last2=Kuruwita |first2=Rathindra |title=Sri Lanka's Supreme Court overturns sacking of parliament |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/12/sri-lanka-supreme-court-overturns-sacking-parliament-181213113720319.html |accessdate=14 December 2018 |agency=Al Jazeera |date=13 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==COVID -19==\nOn March 19, 2020, Sri Lanka reported an increase in COVID-19 pandemic, but the government went ahead with the nominations until March 18, 2020, to close nominations to the elections. <ref>http://www.colombopage.com/archive_20A/Mar19_1584592211CH.php</ref>On March 19 soon after the nominations ended, the elections commission with its powers postpone the elections.<ref>http://www.adaderana.lk/news/61545/sri-lankas-general-election-postponed</ref>\n\n==Electoral system==\n196 MPs were elected from 22 multi-member [[Electoral districts in Sri Lanka|electoral districts]] using the [[D'Hondt method]] with an [[open list]], a [[proportional representation]] system.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Blanc|first1=Jarrett|last2=Hylland|first2=Aanund|last3=Vollan|first3=Kare|title=State Structure and Electoral Systems in Post-Conflict Situations|date=2006|publisher=[[International Foundation for Electoral Systems]]|isbn=1-931459-17-7|page=106|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1EXgwebG5oEC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Report of the Post-Election Assessment of Sri Lanka Mission: November 28 \u2013 December 2, 2000|url=https://www.ndi.org/files/1198_lk_postelect122000.pdf|publisher=[[National Democratic Institute for International Affairs]]|page=10|date=28 December 2000}}</ref> The remaining 29 seats were allocated to contesting [[List of political parties in Sri Lanka|parties]] and [[Independent politician|independent]] groups in proportion to their share of the national vote.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Thilakarathne|first1=N. M. C.|editor1-last=Brian|editor1-first=Rob|title=Parliamentary Libraries and Information Services of Asia and the Pacific: Papers prepared for the 62nd IFLA Conference Beijing, China August 25\u201331, 1996|date=1997|publisher=Walter de Gruyte|isbn=3-11-094763-3|page=87|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rlohAAAAQBAJ|chapter=Parliament Library of Sri Lanka}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sri Lanka: Parliament|url=http://www.ipu.org/parline/reports/2295.htm|publisher=[[Inter-Parliamentary Union]]}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Url|1=parliament.lk|2=Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n* {{Url|1=slelections.gov.lk|2=Department of Elections, Sri Lanka}}\n<references group=\"lower-alpha\" />\n\n{{Sri Lankan elections}}\n\n[[Category:Future elections in Asia|Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Parliamentary elections in Sri Lanka]]\n", "name_user": "Kaltenmeyer", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTimeline:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_Sri_Lankan_parliamentary_election"}
{"title_page": "The Days (song)", "text_new": "{{short description|2014 single by Avicii}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = The Days\n| cover      = The Days cover.png\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Avicii]]\n| EP         = [[The Days / Nights EP]]\n| released   = {{Start date|2014|10|03|df=yes}}\n| format     = {{hlist|[[CD single|CD]]|[[Music download|digital download]]}}\n| recorded   = 2014\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Folktronica]]|[[Soul music|soul]]|[[House music|house]]}}\n| length     = {{ubl|4:38 {{small|(album version)}}|3:45 {{small|(radio edit)}}|5:51 {{small|(extended mix)}}}}\n| label      = {{hlist|PRMD|[[Universal Music Group|Universal]]}}\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Brandon Flowers]]|[[Salem Al Fakir]]|[[Avicii|Tim Bergling]]|[[Robbie Williams]]|[[Vincent Pontare]]}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|Salem Al Fakir|Avicii|Vincent Pontare}}\n| chronology = [[Avicii]]\n| prev_title = [[Dar um Jeito (We Will Find a Way)]]\n| prev_year  = 2014\n| next_title = [[Divine Sorrow]]\n| next_year  = 2014\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[Robbie Williams]]\n | type       = singles\n | prev_title = [[Shine My Shoes]]\n | prev_year  = 2014\n | title      = The Days\n | year       = 2014\n | next_title = [[Party Like a Russian]]\n | next_year  = 2016\n}}\n{{External music video|{{YouTube|JDglMK9sgIQ| \"The Days\" (lyrics video)}} }}\n}}\n\n\"'''The Days'''\" is a song by Swedish DJ and record producer [[Avicii]], with vocals by English singer [[Robbie Williams]]. The song was written by [[Brandon Flowers]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/brandon-flowers-12-1209441|title=Brandon Flowers collaborates with Avicii for new version of \u2018The Days\u2019|website=nme.com}}</ref> [[Robbie Williams]], [[Salem Al Fakir]], Avicii and [[Vincent Pontare]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ascap.com/aceclient/AceClient/#ace/work/887518508|title=IBM Security Access Manager|website=mobile.ascap.com}}</ref> and was produced by Avicii, Fakir and Pontare. The song was played for the first time in [[Boston]], with uncredited vocals by Fakir. The song was released worldwide on 3 October 2014. It was released alongside \"[[The Nights]]\" in ''[[The Days / Nights EP]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/the-days-nights-ep/id943278970|title=The Days/Nights - EP by Avicii|date=1 January 2014|publisher=iTunes}}</ref> A planned release in the United Kingdom on 23 November 2014 was cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fuse.tv/2014/10/avicii-the-days-robbie-williams|title=Avicii Returns With Genre-Defying \"The Days\" ft. U.K. Superstar Robbie Williams|last=Benjamin|first=Jeff|date=3 October 2014|publisher=fuse.tv}}</ref>\n\n==Composition==\n\"The Days\" is written in the key of C major, at a tempo of 127 BPM.<ref>[http://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtd.asp?ppn=MN0140524 Avicii \"The Days\" Sheet Music] musicnotes.com</ref> The chord structure is based on the pop punk chord progression.\n\n==Recording==\nThe song was originally written with Vincent Pontare and Salem Al Fakir, but was meant to be a collaboration between [[Brandon Flowers]] and Avicii, with Flowers providing the vocals. However, due to Flowers' dissatisfaction with the recording, Avicii brought on a different vocalist, Robbie Williams.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/6590204/avicii-brandon-flowers-days-killers|title=Hear Avicii's Awesome Unreleased Jam With the Killers' Brandon Flowers|website=billboard.com}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\nAn official lyric video was also released on [[YouTube]] by the official Avicii [[Vevo]] channel.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JDglMK9sgIQ|title=Avicii - The Days (Lyric Video)}}</ref> In the video, an artist (later confirmed as [[INO (artist)|INO]]),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ino.net|title=INO - Official artist website}}</ref> [[Spray painting|spray-paint]]s the lyrics of \"The Days\" in black against a white wall. Near the end of the video, a pan-out reveals the lyrics creating a portrait of Avicii, which is subsequently covered with splashes of coloured paint by the artist.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/code/6273847/avicii-the-days-lyric-video-exclusive|title=''Billboard'' magazine: Watch Avicii's 'The Days' Lyric Video|date=3 October 2014|work=Billboard}}</ref>\n\nAs of May 2018, the lyric video has been viewed more than 150 million times.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JDglMK9sgIQ|title=Avicii - The Days (Lyric Video)}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Digital download<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/au/album/the-days-single/id922528476|title=The Days - Single by Avicii on Apple Music|website=iTunes|language=en|access-date=2017-02-09}}</ref>\n| title1 = The Days\n| length1 = 4:38\n}}\n\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed = yes\n| headline = CD single<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.universal-music.de/main?url=L2F2aWNpaS9kaXNrb2dyYWZpZS9kZXRhaWwvcHJvZHVjdDoyMjE1ODcvdGhlLWRheXM=&album=221587|title=Universal Music Deutschland: Deine Stars, deine Musik, alle Genres - Universal Music|publisher=}}</ref>\n| title1 = The Days\n| note1 = Radio Edit\n| length1 = 3:45\n| title2 = The Days\n| note2 = Original Mix\n| length2 = 4:38\n| title3 = The Days\n| note3 = Extended Mix\n| length3 = 5:51\n| total_length = 14:14\n}}\n\n==Credits and personnel==\n*[[Brandon Flowers]] \u2013 lyrics, vocals {{small|(demo version only)}} <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Avicii-The-Days/release/6201108|title=Avicii - The Days|website=discogs.com}}</ref>\n*[[Salem Al Fakir]] \u2013 producer, vocals {{small|(demo version only)}}\n*[[Avicii|Tim Bergling]] \u2013 music, producer\n*[[Vincent Pontare]] \u2013 producer\n*[[Robbie Williams]] \u2013 vocals\n*Stuart Hawkes \u2013 mastering\n*Ash Pournouri \u2013 executive producer<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Avicii-The-Days-Nights-EP/release/6369045|title=Avicii - The Days / Nights EP|website=Discogs}}</ref>\n\nCredits adapted from [[CD single]].<ref name=\"credits\">{{cite AV media notes|others=[[Avicii]]|title=The Days|year=2014|type=booklet|publisher=[[Universal Music Group|PM:AM Recordings]]|id=0602547072924}}</ref>\n\n==Charts and certifications==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! Chart (2014\u201315)\n! Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Australia|10|artist=Avicii|song=The Days|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| Australia Dance ([[ARIA Charts|ARIA]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pandora.nla.gov.au/pan/23790/20141022-0924/Issue1286.pdf|title=Week Commencing ~ 20 October 2014 ~ Issue #1286|work=[[Australian Recording Industry Association]]|publisher=[[Pandora Archive]]|date=20 October 2014|accessdate=5 November 2014}}</ref>\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n{{singlechart|Austria|3|artist=Avicii|song=The Days|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders Tip|2|artist=Avicii|song=The Days|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders Dance|9|artist = Avicii|song = The Days|rowheader=true|accessdate=21 November 2014|refname=\"Flanders\"}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Wallonia Tip|2|artist=Avicii|song=The Days|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Wallonia Dance|11|artist = Avicii|song = The Days|rowheader=true|accessdate=7 November 2014|refname=\"Wallonia\"}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Brazil ([[Brasil Hot 100 Airplay|''Billboard'' Brasil Hot 100]])<ref name=\"BRA Bill\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com.br/tipo_lista/top-100/20141206/|title= Top 100 Billboard Brasil - weekly|work= [[Billboard Brasil]] |date= 6 December 2014 |accessdate= 12 December 2014}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|86\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canada|80|artist=Avicii|rowheader=true|accessdate=19 October 2014}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Czech Republic|17|year=2014|week=47|rowheader=true|accessdate=24 November 2014}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Czechdigital|1|year=2014|week=45|rowh