{"title_page": "Tabrez Ansari lynching", "text_new": "{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n| title      = Tabrez Ansari lynching\n| image      =\n| caption    =\n|map= {{Location map|India\n|width = 250\n|float = right\n|label =\n  |marksize = 8\n  | lat_deg = 22.8027\n  | lon_deg = 86.1807\n  }}\n| map_caption = Dhatkidih, Jamshedpur\n| location   = Dhatkidih, [[Jharkhand]], India\n| coordinates =\n| target     = Tabrez Ansari\n| date       = 17 June 2019\n| time       =\n| timezone   =\n| type       = Lynching\n| fatalities = 1 (Tabrez Ansari)\n| perps      = Mob\n| susperps   =\n| weapons    = Blunt objects\n}}\n\nOn 17 June 2019, 24-year-old '''Tabrez Ansari''' was attacked by a [[Mob lynching|lynch mob]] in [[Jharkhand]], India. He was tied to a tree, brutally beaten on suspicion of bike  theft;<ref name=\"video report\">{{Cite web|url=https://m.telegraphindia.com/india/tabrez-assault-clip-showing-chant-not-doctored/cid/1704037|title=Tabrez assault clip showing chant \u2018not doctored\u2019|website=www.telegraphindia.com}}</ref> Ansari, a Muslim, was also forced to chant Hindu sayings. He died several days later, succumbing to the injuries. The incident came to light after a video of the lynching went viral.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-48882053 |title=Jai Shri Ram: The Hindu chant that became a murder cry |date=10 July 2019 |publisher=[[BBC]]}}</ref> India's Prime Minister commented on this lynching in the [[Parliament of India]].\n\n==Events==\nTabrez Ansari was an orphan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/opinion/columns/no-one-killed-tabrez-ansari-lynching-jharkhand-police-5993644/|title=Tabrez Ansari lynching case: Why the outcome must concern us all|date=14 September 2019}}</ref> He lived in [[Pune]] and worked there for seven years.<ref name=\"auto\"/> He visited his hometown of Kadamdih occasionally on festivals. For [[Eid al-Fitr]] he visited Kadamdih.<ref name=\"auto\"/> During the visit, on 17 June, he went to [[Jamshedpur]] with two friends on the bike of one of his friends.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsclick.in/Jharkhand-Lynching-Tabrez-Ansari-Religious-Polarisation|title=After Tabrez Ansari\u2019s Lynching, Attempts at Religious Polarisation Continue in Jharkhand Village|date=28 June 2019|website=NewsClick}}</ref> While returning from Jamshedpur, he was caught in the village Dhatkidih, near Kadamdih. He was tied to a tree by the mob and brutally beaten on the suspicion of bike theft. While the mob was beating him, a video was made by an unidentified person in the mob. He was forced to say religious slogans such as \"[[Jai Shri Ram]]\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/25/world/asia/india-hindu-muslim-beating.html|title=Forced to Chant Hindu Slogans, Muslim Man Is Beaten to Death in India|last=Raj|first=Suhasini|date=2019-06-25|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-04|last2=Nordland|first2=Rod|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and \"Jai [[Hanuman]]\", which translates from Hindi to \"hail Lord Ram\" or \"victory to Lord Ram\".<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/india/lynch-mob-to-victim-chant-jai-shri-ram-and-jai-hanuman-suggests-footage/cid/1693066|title=Lynch mob to victim: Chant \u2018Jai Shri Ram\u2019 and 'Jai Hanuman'|website=www.telegraphindia.com}}</ref>\n\nOn the morning of 18 June, the police were notified. Ansari was arrested and locked up in Saraykela Police Station.<ref name=bbc1>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/hindi/india-48758990|title=\u0924\u092c\u0930\u0947\u091c\u093c \u0905\u0902\u0938\u093e\u0930\u0940 \u0924\u094b \u0917\u093e\u0901\u0935 \u0935\u093e\u0932\u094b\u0902 \u0915\u0947 \u0932\u093f\u090f \u0938\u094b\u0928\u0942 \u0925\u0947, \u092e\u093e\u0930\u0928\u0947 \u0935\u093e\u0932\u0947 \u0915\u094c\u0928?|first=\u0906\u0928\u0902\u0926|last=\u0926\u0924\u094d\u0924|date=25 June 2019|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref> His wife received a call from him telling her what had happened. She informed her relatives.\n\nHis uncle visited the station and saw that he was severely injured. He asked the police to provide medical treatment, but Ansari was sent to prison without it. Two days later. when his uncle went to see him in prison, Ansari was not in any condition to talk. His uncle again contacted the police for medical help, but he was denied. He tried to reach the medical officer of the prison too, but was unable to meet him. On the morning of 22 June, Ansari's family received news that his condition was severe, and he was admitted to Sadar Hospital. His relatives reached the hospital by 7:30 am, but by that time, he died.<ref name=bbc1/>\n\n==Response==\nThe Tabrez family demanded that the perpetrators be tried under Section 302 (Punishment for murder) of the Indian Penal Code.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-jharkhand-lynching-family-of-man-beaten-on-suspicion-of-theft-demands-compensation-job-for-wife-2764534 |title=Jharkhand lynching: Family of man beaten on suspicion of theft demands compensation, job for wife |date=24 June 2019 |newspaper=[[Daily News and Analysis]]}}</ref> Ansari's wife said that her husband was mercilessly beaten because he was a Muslim. She demanded justice.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/jharkhand-mob-killing-five-arrested-so-far-two-cops-suspended-for-negligence-2058442|title=Jharkhand Mob Killing: 11 Men Arrested, 2 Police Officers Suspended|last=Kumar|first=Manish|date=2019-06-05|website=NDTV.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=21 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 June, 11 arrests were made, and two policemen were suspended for \"not reporting the seriousness of the issue to the higher authorities\" and \"{{sic|register}} a case of lynching on the very same day\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/jharkhand-mob-killing-five-arrested-so-far-two-cops-suspended-for-negligence-2058442?amp=1&akamai-rum=off |title=Jharkhand Mob Killing: 11 Men Arrested, 2 Police Officers Suspended |date=25 June 2019 |author=Manish Kumar |newspaper=Daily News and Analysis}}</ref>\n\nAn SIT team was assigned to investigate the case. The Saraikela-Kharsawan district police charged 11 of the 13 named accused in the case on 29 July. The murder charges were then dropped, but later reinstated.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tabrez Ansari lynching case: Police restore murder charge against 11 accused |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/tabrez-ansari-lynching-case-police-restore-murder-charge-against-11-accused-1600603-2019-09-18 |accessdate=20 November 2019 |work=India Today |language=en}}</ref>\n\nA medical panel of five members was formed to look into the death. The resulting medical report concluded that Tabrez Ansari suffered a skull fracture caused by a \"hard and blunt object\", a [[subarachnoid haemorrhage]], and clotting of blood in the lower layer of the skull; and suggests that these injuries led to the [[cardiac arrest]] that resulted in Ansari's death. The consumption of poison was ruled out.<ref name=\"India Today Medical Report\">{{cite news |title=Tabrez Ansari lynching: New medical report suggests cardiac arrest was due to skull fracture, other injuries |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/tabrez-ansari-lynching-medical-report-cardiac-arrest-skull-fracture-jharkhand-police-1598668-2019-09-13 |accessdate=20 November 2019 |work=India Today |language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 September 2019, the police dropped the murder charges by giving cardiac arrest as the reason of death, which led to an uproar.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/murder-charge-dropped-in-tabrez-ansari-lynching-case-in-jharkhand-2303797.html|title=Murder Charge Dropped in Tabrez Ansari Lynching Case in Jharkhand|website=News18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/tabrez-ansari-lynching-police-drop-murder-charges-against-11-citing-autopsy-report-1597490-2019-09-10|title=Tabrez Ansari lynching: Police drop murder charges against 11 citing autopsy report|author=India Today Web Desk New (Input from Satyajeet Kumar)|date= 10 September 2019 |website=India Today}}</ref> Due to this, the police were accused of weakening the case. On 18 September 2019, the police filed a supplementary chargesheet after obtaining the opinion of a board of doctors of [[MGM Medical College and Hospital]], reinstating the murder charges.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/other-states/tabrez-ansari-lynching-case-murder-charge-back-on-all-accused/article29452797.ece |title=Tabrez Ansari lynching case accused face murder charge |date=18 September 2019 |newspaper=[[The Hindu]]}}</ref>\n\nThe lynching resulted in public anger,<ref name=\"Al Jazeera\">{{cite news |title=Protests in Indian cities after Muslim man beaten to death |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/06/protests-indian-cities-muslim-man-beaten-death-190627005534986.html |accessdate=20 November 2019 |work=www.aljazeera.com}}</ref> debates on the use of \"Jai Shri Ram\" as an attack slogan<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-48882053|title=The Hindu chant that became a murder cry|last=Pandey|first=Geeta|date=10 July 2019|work=[[BBC]]|accessdate=20 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and multiple protests, including one in [[New Delhi]] held near the parliament house, where protesters chanted slogans against the [[BJP]] and Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] and demanded an end to anti-Muslim violence.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera\"/>\n\nModi commented on the lynching in parliament, that he was pained<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://in.reuters.com/article/india-protests-lynching-idINKCN1TR2AW|title=Protests in Indian cities after Muslim man is lynched, Modi says he is 'pained'|last=Siddiqui|first=Zeba|date=26 June 2019|website=[[Reuters]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-04}}</ref> to hear about the incident and calling for \"the strictest possible punishment to the accused\".<ref name=\"Al Jazeera\"/>\n\n[[Rahul Gandhi]], at the time President of the [[Indian National Congress]], called the lynching a \"blot on humanity\".<ref name=\"Al Jazeera\"/>\n\n[[Vishwa Hindu Parishad]] called the lynching \"a conspiracy of secularists\",<ref name=\"India Today\">{{cite news |title=VHP brands Tabrez Ansari lynching as conspiracy |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/vhp-brands-tabrez-ansari-lynching-conspiracy-mob-lynching-case-1598037-2019-09-11 |accessdate=20 November 2019 |work=India Today |language=en}}</ref> which VHP Joint General Secretary Surendra Jain blamed on \"the Khan Market Mafia, which has repeatedly been maligning Hindu society, India and humanity.\"<ref name=\"India Today\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Violence against Muslims in India]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Cl6MZG1bcOs Newsreport including filming of lynching] on [[NDTV]], 24 June 2019\n\n[[Category:Lynching deaths in India]]\n[[Category:Anti-Muslim violence in India]]\n[[Category:Riots and civil disorder in India]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n| title      = Tabrez Ansari lynching\n| image      =\n| caption    =\n|map= {{Location map|India\n|width = 250\n|float = right\n|label =\n  |marksize = 8\n  | lat_deg = 22.8027\n  | lon_deg = 86.1807\n  }}\n| map_caption = Dhatkidih, Jamshedpur\n| location   = Dhatkidih, [[Jharkhand]], India\n| coordinates =\n| target     = Tabrez Ansari\n| date       = 17 June 2019\n| time       =\n| timezone   =\n| type       = Lynching\n| fatalities = 1 (Tabrez Ansari)\n| perps      = Mob\n| susperps   =\n| weapons    = Blunt objects\n}}\n\nOn 17 June 2019, 24-year-old '''Tabrez Ansari''' was attacked by a [[Mob lynching|lynch mob]] in [[Jharkhand]], India. He was tied to a tree, brutally beaten on suspicion of bike  theft;<ref name=\"video report\">{{Cite web|url=https://m.telegraphindia.com/india/tabrez-assault-clip-showing-chant-not-doctored/cid/1704037|title=Tabrez assault clip showing chant \u2018not doctored\u2019|website=www.telegraphindia.com}}</ref> Ansari, a Muslim, was also forced to chant Hindu sayings. He died several days later, succumbing to the injuries. The incident came to light after a video of the lynching went viral.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-48882053 |title=Jai Shri Ram: The Hindu chant that became a murder cry |date=10 July 2019 |publisher=[[BBC]]}}</ref> India's Prime Minister commented on this lynching in the [[Parliament of India]].\n\n==Events==\nTabrez Ansari was an orphan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/opinion/columns/no-one-killed-tabrez-ansari-lynching-jharkhand-police-5993644/|title=Tabrez Ansari lynching case: Why the outcome must concern us all|date=14 September 2019}}</ref> He lived in [[Pune]] and worked there for seven years.<ref name=\"auto\"/> He visited his hometown of Kadamdih occasionally on festivals. For [[Eid al-Fitr]] he visited Kadamdih.<ref name=\"auto\"/> During the visit, on 17 June, he went to [[Jamshedpur]] with two friends on the bike of one of his friends.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsclick.in/Jharkhand-Lynching-Tabrez-Ansari-Religious-Polarisation|title=After Tabrez Ansari\u2019s Lynching, Attempts at Religious Polarisation Continue in Jharkhand Village|date=28 June 2019|website=NewsClick}}</ref> While returning from Jamshedpur, he was caught in the village Dhatkidih, near Kadamdih. He was tied to a tree by the mob and brutally beaten on the suspicion of bike theft. While mob was beating him, a video was made by an unidentified person in the mob. He was forced to say religious slogans such as \"[[Jai Shri Ram]]\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/25/world/asia/india-hindu-muslim-beating.html|title=Forced to Chant Hindu Slogans, Muslim Man Is Beaten to Death in India|last=Raj|first=Suhasini|date=2019-06-25|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-04|last2=Nordland|first2=Rod|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and \"Jai [[Hanuman]]\", which translates from Hindi to \"hail Lord Ram\" or \"victory to Lord Ram\".<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/india/lynch-mob-to-victim-chant-jai-shri-ram-and-jai-hanuman-suggests-footage/cid/1693066|title=Lynch mob to victim: Chant \u2018Jai Shri Ram\u2019 and 'Jai Hanuman'|website=www.telegraphindia.com}}</ref>\n\nOn the morning of 18 June, the police were notified. Ansari was arrested and locked up in Saraykela Police Station.<ref name=bbc1>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/hindi/india-48758990|title=\u0924\u092c\u0930\u0947\u091c\u093c \u0905\u0902\u0938\u093e\u0930\u0940 \u0924\u094b \u0917\u093e\u0901\u0935 \u0935\u093e\u0932\u094b\u0902 \u0915\u0947 \u0932\u093f\u090f \u0938\u094b\u0928\u0942 \u0925\u0947, \u092e\u093e\u0930\u0928\u0947 \u0935\u093e\u0932\u0947 \u0915\u094c\u0928?|first=\u0906\u0928\u0902\u0926|last=\u0926\u0924\u094d\u0924|date=25 June 2019|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref> His wife received a call from him telling her what had happened. She informed her relatives.\n\nHis uncle visited the station and saw that he was severely injured. He asked the police to provide medical treatment, but Ansari was sent to prison without it. Two days later. when his uncle went to see him in prison, Ansari was not in any condition to talk. His uncle again contacted the police for medical help, but he was denied. He tried to reach the medical officer of the prison too, but was unable to meet him. On the morning of 22 June, Ansari's family received news that his condition was severe, and he was admitted to Sadar Hospital. His relatives reached the hospital by 7:30 am, but by that time, he died.<ref name=bbc1/>\n\n==Response==\nThe Tabrez family demanded that the perpetrators be tried under Section 302 (Punishment for murder) of the Indian Penal Code.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-jharkhand-lynching-family-of-man-beaten-on-suspicion-of-theft-demands-compensation-job-for-wife-2764534 |title=Jharkhand lynching: Family of man beaten on suspicion of theft demands compensation, job for wife |date=24 June 2019 |newspaper=[[Daily News and Analysis]]}}</ref> Ansari's wife said that her husband was mercilessly beaten because he was a Muslim. She demanded justice.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/jharkhand-mob-killing-five-arrested-so-far-two-cops-suspended-for-negligence-2058442|title=Jharkhand Mob Killing: 11 Men Arrested, 2 Police Officers Suspended|last=Kumar|first=Manish|date=2019-06-05|website=NDTV.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=21 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 June, 11 arrests were made, and two policemen were suspended for \"not reporting the seriousness of the issue to the higher authorities\" and \"{{sic|register}} a case of lynching on the very same day\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/jharkhand-mob-killing-five-arrested-so-far-two-cops-suspended-for-negligence-2058442?amp=1&akamai-rum=off |title=Jharkhand Mob Killing: 11 Men Arrested, 2 Police Officers Suspended |date=25 June 2019 |author=Manish Kumar |newspaper=Daily News and Analysis}}</ref>\n\nAn SIT team was assigned to investigate the case. The Saraikela-Kharsawan district police charged 11 of the 13 named accused in the case on 29 July. The murder charges were then dropped, but later reinstated.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tabrez Ansari lynching case: Police restore murder charge against 11 accused |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/tabrez-ansari-lynching-case-police-restore-murder-charge-against-11-accused-1600603-2019-09-18 |accessdate=20 November 2019 |work=India Today |language=en}}</ref>\n\nA medical panel of five members was formed to look into the death. The resulting medical report concluded that Tabrez Ansari suffered a skull fracture caused by a \"hard and blunt object\", a [[subarachnoid haemorrhage]], and clotting of blood in the lower layer of the skull; and suggests that these injuries led to the [[cardiac arrest]] that resulted in Ansari's death. The consumption of poison was ruled out.<ref name=\"India Today Medical Report\">{{cite news |title=Tabrez Ansari lynching: New medical report suggests cardiac arrest was due to skull fracture, other injuries |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/tabrez-ansari-lynching-medical-report-cardiac-arrest-skull-fracture-jharkhand-police-1598668-2019-09-13 |accessdate=20 November 2019 |work=India Today |language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 September 2019, the police dropped the murder charges by giving cardiac arrest as the reason of death, which led to an uproar.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/murder-charge-dropped-in-tabrez-ansari-lynching-case-in-jharkhand-2303797.html|title=Murder Charge Dropped in Tabrez Ansari Lynching Case in Jharkhand|website=News18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/tabrez-ansari-lynching-police-drop-murder-charges-against-11-citing-autopsy-report-1597490-2019-09-10|title=Tabrez Ansari lynching: Police drop murder charges against 11 citing autopsy report|author=India Today Web Desk New (Input from Satyajeet Kumar)|date= 10 September 2019 |website=India Today}}</ref> Due to this, the police were accused of weakening the case. On 18 September 2019, the police filed a supplementary chargesheet after obtaining the opinion of a board of doctors of [[MGM Medical College and Hospital]], reinstating the murder charges.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/other-states/tabrez-ansari-lynching-case-murder-charge-back-on-all-accused/article29452797.ece |title=Tabrez Ansari lynching case accused face murder charge |date=18 September 2019 |newspaper=[[The Hindu]]}}</ref>\n\nThe lynching resulted in public anger,<ref name=\"Al Jazeera\">{{cite news |title=Protests in Indian cities after Muslim man beaten to death |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/06/protests-indian-cities-muslim-man-beaten-death-190627005534986.html |accessdate=20 November 2019 |work=www.aljazeera.com}}</ref> debates on the use of \"Jai Shri Ram\" as an attack slogan<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-48882053|title=The Hindu chant that became a murder cry|last=Pandey|first=Geeta|date=10 July 2019|work=[[BBC]]|accessdate=20 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and multiple protests, including one in [[New Delhi]] held near the parliament house, where protesters chanted slogans against the [[BJP]] and Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] and demanded an end to anti-Muslim violence.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera\"/>\n\nModi commented on the lynching in parliament, that he was pained<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://in.reuters.com/article/india-protests-lynching-idINKCN1TR2AW|title=Protests in Indian cities after Muslim man is lynched, Modi says he is 'pained'|last=Siddiqui|first=Zeba|date=26 June 2019|website=[[Reuters]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-04}}</ref> to hear about the incident and calling for \"the strictest possible punishment to the accused\".<ref name=\"Al Jazeera\"/>\n\n[[Rahul Gandhi]], at the time President of the [[Indian National Congress]], called the lynching a \"blot on humanity\".<ref name=\"Al Jazeera\"/>\n\n[[Vishwa Hindu Parishad]] called the lynching \"a conspiracy of secularists\",<ref name=\"India Today\">{{cite news |title=VHP brands Tabrez Ansari lynching as conspiracy |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/vhp-brands-tabrez-ansari-lynching-conspiracy-mob-lynching-case-1598037-2019-09-11 |accessdate=20 November 2019 |work=India Today |language=en}}</ref> which VHP Joint General Secretary Surendra Jain blamed on \"the Khan Market Mafia, which has repeatedly been maligning Hindu society, India and humanity.\"<ref name=\"India Today\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Violence against Muslims in India]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Cl6MZG1bcOs Newsreport including filming of lynching] on [[NDTV]], 24 June 2019\n\n[[Category:Lynching deaths in India]]\n[[Category:Anti-Muslim violence in India]]\n[[Category:Riots and civil disorder in India]]\n", "name_user": "Gr\u00e5bergs Gr\u00e5a S\u00e5ng", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEvents", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tabrez_Ansari_lynching"}
{"title_page": "Willie Stevenson", "text_new": "{{Other people|William Stevenson}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Willie Stevenson\n| image          = Willie Stevenson (1966).jpg\n| fullname       = William Stevenson<ref name=\"The Encyclopaedia of Stoke City\"/>\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1939|10|26}}<ref name=\"The Encyclopaedia of Stoke City\"/>\n| birth_place    = [[Leith]], [[Midlothian]], Scotland<ref name=\"The Encyclopaedia of Stoke City\"/>\n| death_date     =\n| position       = [[Midfielder|Left half]]\n| youthyears1    = | youthclubs1=Edina Hearts\n| years1 = 1958\u20131962 | caps1 = 72  | goals1 = 1  | clubs1 = [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]]\n| years2 = 1962\u20131967 | caps2 = 188 | goals2 = 15 | clubs2 = [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]\n| years3 = 1967\u20131973 | caps3 = 94  | goals3 = 5  | clubs3 = [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]]\n| years4 = 1971      | caps4 = 5   | goals4 = 0  | clubs4 = \u2192 [[Hellenic F.C.|Hellenic]] (loan)\n| years5 = 1973\u20131974 | caps5 = 20  | goals5 = 0  | clubs5 = [[Tranmere Rovers F.C.|Tranmere Rovers]]\n| years6 = 1974      | caps6 = 4   | goals6 = 0  | clubs6 = [[Limerick F.C.|Limerick]]\n| years7 = 1974      | caps7 = 19  | goals7 = 0  | clubs7 = [[Vancouver Whitecaps (NASL)|Vancouver Whitecaps]]\n| years8 = 1974\u20131975 | caps8 = 32  | goals8 = 0  | clubs8 = [[Macclesfield Town F.C.|Macclesfield Town]]\n| totalcaps =434 | totalgoals =21\n| nationalyears1 = 1959\n| nationalteam1  = [[Scottish League XI]]\n| nationalcaps1  = 1\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n}}\n\n'''William''' \"'''Willie'''\" '''Stevenson''' (born 26 October 1939) is a Scottish former professional [[association football|football]] player and [[manager (association football)|manager]]. He played for [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]], [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]], [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]], [[Tranmere Rovers F.C.|Tranmere Rovers]]<ref name=\"The Encyclopaedia of Stoke City\">{{cite book|last=Matthews|first=Tony|title=The Encyclopaedia of Stoke City|year=1994|publisher=Lion Press|isbn=0-9524151-0-0}}</ref> and the [[Vancouver Whitecaps (1974\u201384)|Vancouver Whitecaps]].\n\n==Career==\n===Rangers===\nStevenson was born in [[Leith]], [[Midlothian]], Scotland. He played for Edina Hearts, [[Dalkeith Thistle F.C.|Dalkeith Thistle]] and [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] in summer of 1959. He lost his first team place as a first team regular after [[Jim Baxter]] joined Rangers in 1960. Baxter initially played at inside forward before being moved to the left half berth Stevenson had occupied. Rangers then allowed Stevenson to move on loan to Australia when both Liverpool and [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]] put in bids to sign him.\n\n===Liverpool===\n[[Bill Shankly]] paid [[\u00a3]]20,000 to bring the 22-year-old to [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in October 1962. He made his debut in the 2\u20131 home league defeat to [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] on 3 November 1962, he scored his first goal in a 5\u20130 victory over [[Leyton Orient F.C.|Leyton Orient]] at [[Anfield]], Stevenson managed to hit the net in the 35th minute, [[Roger Hunt]] with a [[hat-trick]] and [[Ian St John]] scored the others.<ref name=\"LFC\"/> Stevenson helped the Reds gain the 1963\u201364 [[Football League First Division|First Division]] title in only their 2nd season back in the top flight of English football, he featured in 38 of the 42 league games thus cementing a starting role on the left of the Reds midfield.<ref name=\"LFC\">{{cite web|title=Willie Stevenson|url=http://www.lfchistory.net/Players/Player/Profile/420|work=LFC History|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nHe played a major role in winning of Liverpool's first ever [[FA Cup]] in 1965, he played in all of the ties scoring the second goal from the penalty spot in the 2\u20130 semi-final victory over [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] at [[Villa Park]].<ref name=\"LFC\"/> [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] stood in Shankly's team's way and after a 0\u20130 draw in 90 minutes, goals from Hunt and St John beat the [[Elland Road]] club by 2 goals to 1 to take the trophy go to Anfield after a 72-year wait.<ref name=\"LFC\"/> The following campaign, again, saw silverware head to [[Merseyside]] as the Reds took the league title once more. Stevenson missed just the one fixture and scored five times as Liverpool topped the table by a comfortable 6 points over Leeds. He also tasted disappointment, however, as [[Borussia Dortmund]] beat Liverpool 2\u20131 in the [[Cup Winners Cup|European Cup Winners Cup]] final at [[Hampden Park]], the 1st European final the Anfield club had reached.<ref name=\"LFC\"/>\n\nShankly had bought the 19-year-old [[Emlyn Hughes]] from [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]] in the February 1967 and selected him ahead of Stevenson at the beginning of the 1967\u201368 season, this proved to be turning point in Stevenson's career, he got the nod just once in the league and three times in the [[UEFA Cup|Fairs Cup]]. By December 1967 he was on his way leaving for [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]].<ref name=\"LFC\"/>\n\n===Stoke City===\nStoke manager [[Tony Waddington]] paid \u00a330,000 for Stevenson as a replacement for the departed [[Calvin Palmer]].<ref name=\"The Encyclopaedia of Stoke City\"/> He played 20 games in [[1967\u201368 Stoke City F.C. season|1967\u201368]] and 34 times in [[1968\u201369 Stoke City F.C. season|1968\u201369]] as Stoke had two poor seasons narrowly avoiding relegation. A much improved [[1969\u201370 Stoke City F.C. season|1969\u201370]] campaign saw Stevenson play 23 games as Stoke finished in 9th.<ref name=\"The Encyclopaedia of Stoke City\"/> He played six matches at the start of [[1970\u201371 Stoke City F.C. season|1970\u201371]] before injury ruled him out for the remainder of the season.<ref name=\"The Encyclopaedia of Stoke City\"/> He played 25 games in [[1971\u201372 Stoke City F.C. season|1971\u201372]] and just three in [[1972\u201373 Stoke City F.C. season|1972\u201373]].<ref name=\"The Encyclopaedia of Stoke City\"/> At the end of the season he left the [[Victoria Ground]] after making 111 appearances scoring seven goals.\n\n===Tranmere Rovers===\n\nHe joined [[Football League Third Division|Third Division]] [[Tranmere Rovers F.C.|Tranmere Rovers]] where he made 27 appearances.<ref name=\"The Encyclopaedia of Stoke City\"/>\n\n===Later career===\n\nIn 1974, he joined the [[Vancouver Whitecaps (NASL)|Vancouver Whitecaps]] in the newly formed [[North American Soccer League (1968\u20131984)|North American Soccer League]] (NASL). He played in Vancouver for one season.<ref name=forg>[https://www.thisisanfield.com/2008/09/forgotten-hero-willie-stevenson/ \"Forgotten Hero: Willie Stevenson\" thisisanfield.com 10 September 2008]</ref>\n\nHe then played for Limerick<ref name=\"LFC\"/> before returning to the UK to play for non-league [[Macclesfield Town]]. He also spent a short time in South Africa playing for Hellenic.<ref name=forg/>\n\n===After football===\n\nHe spent time as a publican and then ran a [[commercial cleaning|contract cleaning]] company in [[Macclesfield]] where he lived.\n\n==Career statistics==\nSource:<ref>{{ENFA}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|FA Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|League Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Europe\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other{{ref label|Other|A|}}\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"|[[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]]\n|[[1958\u201359 in Scottish football|1958\u201359]]\n|[[Scottish Football League|Scottish Division One]]\n|26||0||3||0||0||0||0||0||0||0||29||0\n|-\n|[[1959\u201360 in Scottish football|1959\u201360]]\n|Scottish Division One\n|33||1||7||0||5||0||9||0||3||0||57||1\n|-\n|[[1960\u201361 in Scottish football|1960\u201361]]\n|Scottish Division One\n|8||0||1||0||2||0||0||0||1||0||12||0\n|-\n|[[1961\u201362 in Scottish football|1961\u201362]]\n|Scottish Division One\n|5||0||1||0||2||0||0||0||0||0||8||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!72!!1!!12!!0!!9!!0!!9!!0!!4!!0!!106!!1\n|-\n|rowspan=\"7\"|[[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]\n|[[1962\u201363 in English football|1962\u201363]]\n|[[Football League First Division|First Division]]\n|28||2||6||0||0||0||0||0||0||0||34||2\n|-\n|[[1963\u201364 in English football|1963\u201364]]\n|First Division\n|38||1||5||0||0||0||0||0|||0||0||43||1\n|-\n|[[1964\u201365 in English football|1964\u201365]]\n|First Division\n|39||3||8||1||0||0||9||1||1||0||57||5\n|-\n|[[1965\u201366 in English football|1965\u201366]]\n|First Division\n|41||5||1||0||0||0||9||1||1||0||52||5\n|-\n|[[1966\u201367 in English football|1966\u201367]]\n|First Division\n|41||3||4||0||0||0||5||0||1||0||51||3\n|-\n|[[1967\u201368 in English football|1967\u201368]]\n|First Division\n|1||1||0||0||0||0||3||0||0||0||4||1\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!188!!15!!24!!1!!0!!0!!26!!2!!3!!0!!241!!18\n|-\n|rowspan=\"7\"|[[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]]\n|[[1967\u201368 Stoke City F.C. season|1967\u201368]]\n|First Division\n|18||0||2||1||0||0||0||0||0||0||20||1\n|-\n|[[1968\u201369 Stoke City F.C. season|1968\u201369]]\n|First Division\n|32||3||0||0||2||0||0||0||0||0||34||3\n|-\n|[[1969\u201370 Stoke City F.C. season|1969\u201370]]\n|First Division\n|20||2||3||1||0||0||0||0||0||0||23||3\n|-\n|[[1970\u201371 Stoke City F.C. season|1970\u201371]]\n|First Division\n|5||0||0||0||1||0||0||0||0||0||6||0\n|-\n|[[1971\u201372 Stoke City F.C. season|1971\u201372]]\n|First Division\n|17||0||0||0||1||0||0||0||8||0||26||0\n|-\n|[[1972\u201373 Stoke City F.C. season|1972\u201373]]\n|First Division\n|2||0||0||0||1||0||0||0||0||0||3||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!94!!5!!5!!2!!5!!0!!0!!0!!8!!0!!112!!7\n|-\n|[[Tranmere Rovers F.C.|Tranmere Rovers]]\n|[[1973\u201374 in English football|1973\u201374]]\n|[[Football League Third Division|Third Division]]\n|20||0||2||0||5||0||0||0|||0||0||27||0\n|-\n|[[Vancouver Whitecaps (1974\u201384)|Vancouver Whitecaps]]\n|[[1974 North American Soccer League season|1974]]\n|[[North American Soccer League (1968\u201384)|North American Soccer League]]\n|19||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||19||0\n|-\n|[[Macclesfield Town F.C.|Macclesfield Town]]\n|[[1974\u201375 Northern Premier League|1974\u201375]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Cheshire League - 1974\u201375 |url=http://silkmenarchives.org.uk/season_stats/npl/1974_75.html |website=Silkmen Archive}}</ref>\n|[[Northern Premier League]]\n|32||0||2||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||8||0||42||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career Total\n!425!!21!!45!!3!!19!!0!!35!!2!!23!!0!!547!!26\n|}\n\n{{refbegin}}\n:A.&nbsp;{{note|Other}} The \"Other\" column constitutes appearances and goals in the [[Anglo-Scottish Cup]], [[Glasgow Cup]], [[FA Community Shield|FA Charity Shield]] and [[Texaco Cup]].\n{{refend}}\n\n==Honours==\n; Liverpool\n* [[Football League First Division]] champions: [[1963\u201364 in English football|1963\u201364]], [[1965\u201366 in English football|1965\u201366]]\n* [[FA Cup]] winners: [[1965 FA Cup Final|1965]]\n* [[FA Community Shield|FA Charity Shield]] winners: [[1964 FA Charity Shield|1964]], [[1965 FA Charity Shield|1965]], [[1966 FA Charity Shield|1966]]\n* [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup]] runners-up: [[1966 European Cup Winners' Cup Final|1966]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{NeilBrownPlayers|player1/williestevenson}}\n* [http://www.lfchistory.net/player_profile.asp?player_id=420 Player profile at LFChistory.net]\n* [http://www.londonhearts.com/SFL/players/billystevenson.html Scotland stats] at londonhearts.com\n\n{{Macclesfield Town F.C. managers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stevenson, Willie}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Leith]]\n[[Category:Rangers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Liverpool F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Stoke City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Tranmere Rovers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Macclesfield Town F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Scottish football managers]]\n[[Category:Association football wing halves]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League representative players]]\n[[Category:Vancouver Whitecaps (1974\u20131984) players]]\n[[Category:Scottish expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate soccer players in Canada]]\n[[Category:North American Soccer League (1968\u20131984) players]]\n[[Category:Dalkeith Thistle F.C. players]]\n[[Category:People educated at Ainslie Park High School]]\n[[Category:Scottish expatriate sportspeople in Canada]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other people|William Stevenson}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Willie Stevenson\n| image          = Willie Stevenson (1966).jpg\n| fullname       = William Stevenson<ref name=\"The Encyclopaedia of Stoke City\"/>\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1939|10|26}}<ref name=\"The Encyclopaedia of Stoke City\"/>\n| birth_place    = [[Leith]], [[Midlothian]], [[Scotland]]<ref name=\"The Encyclopaedia of Stoke City\"/>\n| death_date     =\n| position       = [[Midfielder|Left half]]\n| youthyears1    = \u2013| youthclubs1=Edina Hearts\n| years1 = 1958\u20131962 | caps1 = 72  | goals1 = 1  | clubs1 = [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]]\n| years2 = 1962\u20131967 | caps2 = 188 | goals2 = 15 | clubs2 = [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]\n| years3 = 1967\u20131973 | caps3 = 94  | goals3 = 5  | clubs3 = [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]]\n| years4 = 1971      | caps4 = 5   | goals4 = 0  | clubs4 = \u2192 [[Hellenic F.C.|Hellenic]] (loan)\n| years5 = 1973\u20131974 | caps5 = 20  | goals5 = 0  | clubs5 = [[Tranmere Rovers F.C.|Tranmere Rovers]]\n| years6 = 1974      | caps6 = 4   | goals6 = 0  | clubs6 = [[Limerick F.C.|Limerick]]\n| years7 = 1974      | caps7 = 19  | goals7 = 0  | clubs7 = [[Vancouver Whitecaps (NASL)|Vancouver Whitecaps]]\n| years8 = 1974\u20131975 | caps8 = 32  | goals8 = 0  | clubs8 = [[Macclesfield Town F.C.|Macclesfield Town]]\n| totalcaps =434 | totalgoals =21\n| nationalyears1 = 1959\n| nationalteam1  = [[Scottish League XI]]\n| nationalcaps1  = 1\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n}}\n\n'''William''' \"'''Willie'''\" '''Stevenson''' (born 26 October 1939) is a [[Scotland|Scottish]] former professional [[association football|football]] player and [[manager (association football)|manager]]. He played for [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]], [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]], [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]], [[Tranmere Rovers F.C.|Tranmere Rovers]]<ref name=\"The Encyclopaedia of Stoke City\">{{cite book|last=Matthews|first=Tony|title=The Encyclopaedia of Stoke City|year=1994|publisher=Lion Press|isbn=0-9524151-0-0}}</ref> and the [[Vancouver Whitecaps (1974\u201384)|Vancouver Whitecaps]].\n\n==Career==\n===Rangers===\nStevenson was born in [[Leith]], [[Midlothian]], [[Scotland]]. He played for Edina Hearts, [[Dalkeith Thistle F.C.|Dalkeith Thistle]] and [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] in summer of 1959. He lost his first team place as a first team regular after [[Jim Baxter]] joined Rangers in 1960. Baxter initially played at inside forward before being moved to the left half berth Stevenson had occupied. Rangers then allowed Stevenson to move on loan to Australia when both Liverpool and [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]] put in bids to sign him.\n\n===Liverpool===\n[[Bill Shankly]] paid [[\u00a3]]20,000 to bring the 22-year-old to [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in October 1962. He made his debut in the 2\u20131 home league defeat to [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] on 3 November 1962, he scored his first goal in a 5\u20130 victory over [[Leyton Orient F.C.|Leyton Orient]] at [[Anfield]], Stevenson managed to hit the net in the 35th minute, [[Roger Hunt]] with a [[hat-trick]] and [[Ian St John]] scored the others.<ref name=\"LFC\"/> Stevenson helped the Reds gain the 1963\u201364 [[Football League First Division|First Division]] title in only their 2nd season back in the top flight of [[England|English]] football, he featured in 38 of the 42 league games thus cementing a starting role on the left of the Reds midfield.<ref name=\"LFC\">{{cite web|title=Willie Stevenson|url=http://www.lfchistory.net/Players/Player/Profile/420|work=LFC History|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nHe played a major role in winning of Liverpool's first ever [[FA Cup]] in 1965, he played in all of the ties scoring the second goal from the penalty spot in the 2\u20130 semi-final victory over [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] at [[Villa Park]].<ref name=\"LFC\"/> [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] stood in Shankly's team's way and after a 0\u20130 draw in 90 minutes, goals from Hunt and St John beat the [[Elland Road]] club by 2 goals to 1 to take the trophy go to Anfield after a 72-year wait.<ref name=\"LFC\"/> The following campaign, again, saw silverware head to [[Merseyside]] as the Reds took the league title once more. Stevenson missed just the one fixture and scored five times as Liverpool topped the table by a comfortable 6 points over Leeds. He also tasted disappointment, however, as [[Borussia Dortmund]] beat Liverpool 2\u20131 in the [[Cup Winners Cup|European Cup Winners Cup]] final at [[Hampden Park]], the 1st European final the Anfield club had reached.<ref name=\"LFC\"/>\n\nShankly had bought the 19-year-old [[Emlyn Hughes]] from [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]] in the February 1967 and selected him ahead of Stevenson at the beginning of the 1967\u201368 season, this proved to be turning point in Stevenson's career, he got the nod just once in the league and three times in the [[UEFA Cup|Fairs Cup]]. By December 1967 he was on his way leaving for [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]].<ref name=\"LFC\"/>\n\n===Stoke City===\nStoke manager [[Tony Waddington]] paid \u00a330,000 for Stevenson as a replacement for the departed [[Calvin Palmer]].<ref name=\"The Encyclopaedia of Stoke City\"/> He played 20 games in [[1967\u201368 Stoke City F.C. season|1967\u201368]] and 34 times in [[1968\u201369 Stoke City F.C. season|1968\u201369]] as Stoke had two poor seasons narrowly avoiding relegation. A much improved [[1969\u201370 Stoke City F.C. season|1969\u201370]] campaign saw Stevenson play 23 games as Stoke finished in 9th.<ref name=\"The Encyclopaedia of Stoke City\"/> He played six matches at the start of [[1970\u201371 Stoke City F.C. season|1970\u201371]] before injury ruled him out for the remainder of the season.<ref name=\"The Encyclopaedia of Stoke City\"/> He played 25 games in [[1971\u201372 Stoke City F.C. season|1971\u201372]] and just three in [[1972\u201373 Stoke City F.C. season|1972\u201373]].<ref name=\"The Encyclopaedia of Stoke City\"/> At the end of the season he left the [[Victoria Ground]] after making 111 appearances scoring seven goals.\n\n===Tranmere Rovers===\n\nHe joined [[Football League Third Division|Third Division]] [[Tranmere Rovers F.C.|Tranmere Rovers]] where he made 27 appearances.<ref name=\"The Encyclopaedia of Stoke City\"/>\n\n===Later career===\n\nIn 1974, he joined the [[Vancouver Whitecaps (NASL)|Vancouver Whitecaps]] in the newly formed [[North American Soccer League (1968\u20131984)|North American Soccer League]] (NASL). He played in Vancouver for one season.<ref name=forg>[https://www.thisisanfield.com/2008/09/forgotten-hero-willie-stevenson/ \"Forgotten Hero: Willie Stevenson\" thisisanfield.com 10 September 2008]</ref>\n\nHe then played for Limerick<ref name=\"LFC\"/> before returning to the UK to play for non-league [[Macclesfield Town]]. He also spent a short time in South Africa playing for Hellenic.<ref name=forg/>\n\n===After football===\n\nHe spent time as a publican and then ran a [[commercial cleaning|contract cleaning]] company in [[Macclesfield]] where he lived.\n\n==Career statistics==\nSource:<ref>{{ENFA}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!r