0||34||3\n|-\n|[[1969\u201370 Stoke City F.C. season|1969\u201370]]\n|First Division\n|20||2||3||1||0||0||0||0||0||0||23||3\n|-\n|[[1970\u201371 Stoke City F.C. season|1970\u201371]]\n|First Division\n|5||0||0||0||1||0||0||0||0||0||6||0\n|-\n|[[1971\u201372 Stoke City F.C. season|1971\u201372]]\n|First Division\n|17||0||0||0||1||0||0||0||8||0||26||0\n|-\n|[[1972\u201373 Stoke City F.C. season|1972\u201373]]\n|First Division\n|2||0||0||0||1||0||0||0||0||0||3||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!94!!5!!5!!2!!5!!0!!0!!0!!8!!0!!112!!7\n|-\n|[[Tranmere Rovers F.C.|Tranmere Rovers]]\n|[[1973\u201374 in English football|1973\u201374]]\n|[[Football League Third Division|Third Division]]\n|20||0||2||0||5||0||0||0|||0||0||27||0\n|-\n|[[Vancouver Whitecaps (1974\u201384)|Vancouver Whitecaps]]\n|[[1974 North American Soccer League season|1974]]\n|[[North American Soccer League (1968\u201384)|North American Soccer League]]\n|19||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||19||0\n|-\n|[[Macclesfield Town F.C.|Macclesfield Town]]\n|[[1974\u201375 Northern Premier League|1974\u201375]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Cheshire League - 1974\u201375 |url=http://silkmenarchives.org.uk/season_stats/npl/1974_75.html |website=Silkmen Archive}}</ref>\n|[[Northern Premier League]]\n|32||0||2||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||8||0||42||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career Total\n!425!!21!!45!!3!!19!!0!!35!!2!!23!!0!!547!!26\n|}\n\n{{refbegin}}\n:A.&nbsp;{{note|Other}} The \"Other\" column constitutes appearances and goals in the [[Anglo-Scottish Cup]], [[Glasgow Cup]], [[FA Community Shield|FA Charity Shield]] and [[Texaco Cup]].\n{{refend}}\n\n==Honours==\n; Liverpool\n* [[Football League First Division]] champions: [[1963\u201364 in English football|1963\u201364]], [[1965\u201366 in English football|1965\u201366]]\n* [[FA Cup]] winners: [[1965 FA Cup Final|1965]]\n* [[FA Community Shield|FA Charity Shield]] winners: [[1964 FA Charity Shield|1964]], [[1965 FA Charity Shield|1965]], [[1966 FA Charity Shield|1966]]\n* [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup]] runners-up: [[1966 European Cup Winners' Cup Final|1966]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{NeilBrownPlayers|player1/williestevenson}}\n* [http://www.lfchistory.net/player_profile.asp?player_id=420 Player profile at LFChistory.net]\n* [http://www.londonhearts.com/SFL/players/billystevenson.html Scotland stats] at londonhearts.com\n\n{{Macclesfield Town F.C. managers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stevenson, Willie}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Leith]]\n[[Category:Rangers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Liverpool F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Stoke City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Tranmere Rovers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Macclesfield Town F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Scottish football managers]]\n[[Category:Association football wing halves]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League representative players]]\n[[Category:Vancouver Whitecaps (1974\u20131984) players]]\n[[Category:Scottish expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate soccer players in Canada]]\n[[Category:North American Soccer League (1968\u20131984) players]]\n[[Category:Dalkeith Thistle F.C. players]]\n[[Category:People educated at Ainslie Park High School]]\n[[Category:Scottish expatriate sportspeople in Canada]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Willie_Stevenson"}
{"title_page": "Debbie Grossman", "text_new": "'''Debbie Grossman''' is a Brooklyn-based photographer<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/3776567/for-women-only-re-imagining-russell-lees-pie-town/|title=For Women Only: Re-imagining Russell Lee's Pie Town|last=Goto|first=Yumi|website=Time|language=en-us|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref> from Rochester, NY<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lens.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/06/13/examining-identity-one-gender-at-a-time/|title=Examining Identity, Gender Image by Gender Image|last=MacDonald|first=Kerri|date=2013-06-13|website=Lens Blog|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref> interested in playing with time, re-imagining history, and reviving archival images and documents.\n\n==Education==\nGrossman received an MFA in Photography, Video, and Related Media from the [[School of Visual Arts]], where she won the Paula Rhodes Memorial Prize, and holds a BA in Women\u2019s Studies and Art History from [[Barnard College]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brooklynmuseum.org/eascfa/about/feminist_art_base/debbie-grossman|title=Brooklyn Museum: Debbie Grossman|website=www.brooklynmuseum.org|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nGrossman is a senior editor<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.popphoto.com/authors/debbie-grossman/|title=Debbie Grossman|website=Popular Photography|language=en|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref> at ''[[Popular Photography]]'' magazine, where she is the resident expert on image editing software and technique. Her work is in the collection of the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] and the [[Jewish Museum]], among others. She is represented by the Julie Saul Gallery, New York.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://debbiegrossman.com/index.php?/about-this-site/|title=About : DEBBIE GROSSMAN|website=debbiegrossman.com|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref> In her 2011 show, ''My Pie Town,'' Debbie Grossman created her best known body of work by manipulating photographs first created by [[Russell Lee (photographer)|Russell Lee]]' of a small community of homesteaders in Pie Town, New Mexico.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.inthein-between.com/debbie-grossman-my-pie-town/|title=Debbie Grossman- My Pie Town|date=2013-03-02|website=In the In-Between|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n\n== My Pie Town ==\n''My Pie Town'' first showed at Julie Saul Gallery from April 14 - May 21, 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://juliesaulprojects.com/exhibition-history/2011/my-pie-town/images|title=Julie Saul Projects - My Pie Town - Images|website=juliesaulprojects.com|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref> In these images, Grossman reworks and re-imagines a body of images originally photographed by [[Russell Lee (photographer)|Russell Lee]] for the United States Farm Security Administration in 1940. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.readingthepictures.org/2011/05/history-and-herstory-pie-town-pics-revisited/|title=History and Herstory: Pie Town Pics Revisited|date=2011-05-26|website=Reading The Pictures|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>Using Photoshop to modify Lee\u2019s pictures, Grossman created an imaginary, parallel world - a \"Pie Town\" populated and governed exclusively by women.[http://debbiegrossman.com/index.php?/projects/my-pie-town/] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.inthein-between.com/debbie-grossman-my-pie-town/|title=Debbie Grossman- My Pie Town|date=2013-03-02|website=In the In-Between|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gupmagazine.com/portfolios/my-pie-town|title=My Pie Town|last=x-publishers|website=www.gupmagazine.com|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n\nGrossman first saw the Lee\u2019s Pie Town pictures in the book ''Bound For Glory'' and obtained high resolution public domain versions of them on the [[Library of Congress]] website.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://themorningnews.org/gallery/my-pie-town|title=My Pie Town|last=www.themorningnews.org|first=The Morning News LLC;|website=The Morning News|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref> Using sixteen of Lee\u2019s unpublished series on Pietown, a homesteaded community in New Mexico, Grossman took male bodies and rendered them to look like masculine women; in others, she shifted the body language of pairs of women, bringing them closer to create a sense of intimacy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brooklynmuseum.org/eascfa/about/feminist_art_base/debbie-grossman|title=Brooklyn Museum: Debbie Grossman|website=www.brooklynmuseum.org|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>  The images are revised in subtle ways, making the reading of them very complicated and compelling. Grossman says of the project \"I\u2019ve begun to think of Photoshop as my medium \u2013 I\u2019m fascinated by the fact this it shares qualities with both photography and drawing\u2026..I enjoy imagining My Pie Town working as its own kind of (lighthearted) propaganda\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://juliesaulprojects.com/exhibition-history/2011/my-pie-town/show:press|title=Julie Saul Projects - 2011 - My Pie Town|website=juliesaulprojects.com|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>    ...\"[Lee's] pictures of the town are tinged with his mythologizing of a difficult way of life and the land-conquering kind of patriotism that\u2019s a foundation of the American story. I share Lee\u2019s nostalgia. Seventy years later, I am drawn to a similar utopian ideal. ... I\u2019ve had a lifelong obsession with frontier life. I fantasize about locating myself within those pictures and that time. So in an attempt to make the history I wish was real, I have made over Pie Town to mirror my fantasy.\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.c4fap.org/tag/debbie-grossman/|title=Debbie Grossman Archives|website=The Center for Fine Art Photography|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n\n== Exhibitions ==\n\n=== Solo exhibitions ===\n''My Pie Town,'' Julie Saul Gallery (2011)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://juliesaulprojects.com/exhibition-history/2011/my-pie-town/images|title=Julie Saul Projects - My Pie Town - Images|website=juliesaulprojects.com|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n\n=== Group exhibitions ===\n''Composed: Identity, Politics, Sex'', [[Jewish Museum (Manhattan)|The Jewish Museum]], (2012)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thejewishmuseum.org/exhibitions/composed-identity-politics-sex|title=The Jewish Museum|website=thejewishmuseum.org|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n\n''The Gender Show,'' [[George Eastman Museum|Eastman Museum]] (2013)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eastman.org/my-pie-town|title=My Pie Town {{!}} George Eastman Museum|website=www.eastman.org|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n\n''After Photoshop : Manipulated Photography in the Digital Age,'' [[Metropolitan Museum of Art|The Metropolitan Museum]] 5th Ave (2013)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metmuseum.org/press/exhibitions/2012/after-photoshop|website=www.metmuseum.org|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n\n''FRAMING DESIRE: Photography and Video'', The Modern Art Museum of Fort Worth (2015)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.themodern.org/exhibition/1119|title=FRAMING DESIRE: Photography and Video {{!}} Modern Art Museum of Fort Worth|website=www.themodern.org|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{catimprove|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grossman, Debbie}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Artists from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Barnard College alumni]]\n[[Category:School of Visual Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Rochester, New York]]\n[[Category:Photographers]]\n[[Category:Contemporary artists]]\n", "text_old": "'''Debbie Grossman''' is a Brooklyn-based artist<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/3776567/for-women-only-re-imagining-russell-lees-pie-town/|title=For Women Only: Re-imagining Russell Lee's Pie Town|last=Goto|first=Yumi|website=Time|language=en-us|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref> from Rochester, NY<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lens.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/06/13/examining-identity-one-gender-at-a-time/|title=Examining Identity, Gender Image by Gender Image|last=MacDonald|first=Kerri|date=2013-06-13|website=Lens Blog|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref> interested in playing with time, re-imagining history, and reviving archival images and documents.\n\n==Early years==\nGrossman received an MFA in Photography, Video, and Related Media from the [[School of Visual Arts]], where she won the Paula Rhodes Memorial Prize, and holds a BA in Women\u2019s Studies and Art History from [[Barnard College]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brooklynmuseum.org/eascfa/about/feminist_art_base/debbie-grossman|title=Brooklyn Museum: Debbie Grossman|website=www.brooklynmuseum.org|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nGrossman is a senior editor<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.popphoto.com/authors/debbie-grossman/|title=Debbie Grossman|website=Popular Photography|language=en|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref> at ''[[Popular Photography]]'' magazine, where she is the resident expert on image editing software and technique. Her work is in the collection of the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] and the [[Jewish Museum]], among others. She is represented by the Julie Saul Gallery, New York.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://debbiegrossman.com/index.php?/about-this-site/|title=About : DEBBIE GROSSMAN|website=debbiegrossman.com|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref> In her 2011 show, ''My Pie Town,'' Debbie Grossman created her best known body of work by manipulating photographs first created by [[Russell Lee (photographer)|Russell Lee]]' of a small community of homesteaders in Pie Town, New Mexico.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.inthein-between.com/debbie-grossman-my-pie-town/|title=Debbie Grossman- My Pie Town|date=2013-03-02|website=In the In-Between|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n\n=== My Pie Town ===\n''My Pie Town'' first showed at Julie Saul Gallery from April 14 - May 21, 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://juliesaulprojects.com/exhibition-history/2011/my-pie-town/images|title=Julie Saul Projects - My Pie Town - Images|website=juliesaulprojects.com|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref> In these images, Grossman reworks and re-imagines a body of images originally photographed by [[Russell Lee (photographer)|Russell Lee]] for the United States Farm Security Administration in 1940. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.readingthepictures.org/2011/05/history-and-herstory-pie-town-pics-revisited/|title=History and Herstory: Pie Town Pics Revisited|date=2011-05-26|website=Reading The Pictures|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>Using Photoshop to modify Lee\u2019s pictures, Grossman created an imaginary, parallel world - a \"Pie Town\" populated and governed exclusively by women.[http://debbiegrossman.com/index.php?/projects/my-pie-town/] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.inthein-between.com/debbie-grossman-my-pie-town/|title=Debbie Grossman- My Pie Town|date=2013-03-02|website=In the In-Between|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gupmagazine.com/portfolios/my-pie-town|title=My Pie Town|last=x-publishers|website=www.gupmagazine.com|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n\nGrossman first saw the Lee\u2019s Pie Town pictures in the book ''Bound For Glory'' and obtained high resolution public domain versions of them on the [[Library of Congress]] website.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://themorningnews.org/gallery/my-pie-town|title=My Pie Town|last=www.themorningnews.org|first=The Morning News LLC;|website=The Morning News|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref> Using sixteen of Lee\u2019s unpublished series on Pietown, a homesteaded community in New Mexico, Grossman took male bodies and rendered them to look like masculine women; in others, she shifted the body language of pairs of women, bringing them closer to create a sense of intimacy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brooklynmuseum.org/eascfa/about/feminist_art_base/debbie-grossman|title=Brooklyn Museum: Debbie Grossman|website=www.brooklynmuseum.org|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>  The images are revised in subtle ways, making the reading of them very complicated and compelling. Grossman says of the project \"I\u2019ve begun to think of Photoshop as my medium \u2013 I\u2019m fascinated by the fact this it shares qualities with both photography and drawing\u2026..I enjoy imagining My Pie Town working as its own kind of (lighthearted) propaganda\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://juliesaulprojects.com/exhibition-history/2011/my-pie-town/show:press|title=Julie Saul Projects - 2011 - My Pie Town|website=juliesaulprojects.com|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>    ...\"[Lee's] pictures of the town are tinged with his mythologizing of a difficult way of life and the land-conquering kind of patriotism that\u2019s a foundation of the American story. I share Lee\u2019s nostalgia. Seventy years later, I am drawn to a similar utopian ideal. ... I\u2019ve had a lifelong obsession with frontier life. I fantasize about locating myself within those pictures and that time. So in an attempt to make the history I wish was real, I have made over Pie Town to mirror my fantasy.\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.c4fap.org/tag/debbie-grossman/|title=Debbie Grossman Archives|website=The Center for Fine Art Photography|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n\n== Exhibitions ==\n\n=== Solo exhibitions ===\n''My Pie Town,'' Julie Saul Gallery (2011)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://juliesaulprojects.com/exhibition-history/2011/my-pie-town/images|title=Julie Saul Projects - My Pie Town - Images|website=juliesaulprojects.com|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n\n=== Group exhibitions ===\n''Composed: Identity, Politics, Sex'', [[Jewish Museum (Manhattan)|The Jewish Museum]], (2012)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thejewishmuseum.org/exhibitions/composed-identity-politics-sex|title=The Jewish Museum|website=thejewishmuseum.org|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n\n''The Gender Show,'' [[George Eastman Museum|Eastman Museum]] (2013)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eastman.org/my-pie-town|title=My Pie Town {{!}} George Eastman Museum|website=www.eastman.org|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n\n''After Photoshop : Manipulated Photography in the Digital Age,'' [[Metropolitan Museum of Art|The Metropolitan Museum]] 5th Ave (2013)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metmuseum.org/press/exhibitions/2012/after-photoshop|website=www.metmuseum.org|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n\n''FRAMING DESIRE: Photography and Video'', The Modern Art Museum of Fort Worth (2015)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.themodern.org/exhibition/1119|title=FRAMING DESIRE: Photography and Video {{!}} Modern Art Museum of Fort Worth|website=www.themodern.org|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{catimprove|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grossman, Debbie}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Artists from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Barnard College alumni]]\n[[Category:School of Visual Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Rochester, New York]]\n[[Category:Photographers]]\n[[Category:Contemporary artists]]\n", "name_user": "Rufustbarley", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly years:additional headings and grammatical changes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Debbie_Grossman"}
{"title_page": "Islamophobia in the media", "text_new": "{{Islamophobia}}\n'''Islamophobia in the media''' refers to the occurrence or perception that media outlets tend to cover Muslims or Islam-related topics in a negative light. [[Islamophobia]] is defined as \"Intense dislike or fear of [[Islam]], esp. as a political force; hostility or prejudice towards [[Muslims]]\".<ref name=OED>{{cite web|url=http://www.oed.com/view/Entry/248449?|publisher=Oxford University Press|title=Oxford English Dictionary: Islamophobia}}{{paywall}}</ref><ref>See also:\n* {{cite web|title=Islamophobia|url=https://en.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/islamophobia|website=en.oxforddictionaries.com|accessdate=10 November 2016}}\n* {{cite web|title=Islamophobia|url=http://www.dictionary.com/browse/islamophobia|website=dictionary.com|accessdate=10 November 2016}}\n* {{cite web|title=Islamophobia|url=http://www.collinsdictionary.com/dictionary/english/islamophobia|website=collinsdictionary.com}}</ref>\n\n== Historical context ==\nSome researchers point to the [[Iranian Revolution]] in 1979 as a starting point for Islamophobia in the United States. It may be due to the growing influence of [[Islamism|political Islam]] around the same period. In his book, ''The Modern Middle East'', author Mehran Kamrava notes that the \"rise in the popularity and spread of political Islam can be traced to the 1980s and even earlier, when a general trend in the politicization of Islam began sweeping across the Middle East following the Arab 'victory' in the [[Yom Kippur War|1973 War]] and the success of the Iranian revolution.\"<ref name=Kamrava>{{cite book|last1=Kamrava|first1=Mehran|title=The Modern Middle East|date=2013|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley, California|isbn=978-0-520-27781-6|page=314|edition=Third}}</ref> Others find Islamophobia present in the United States far earlier and argue that Americans were using the fear of Islam as a unifying concept in defining America. Some also believe that the phenomenon of Islamophobia is a psychological defense mechanism, which is spreading through mass media like a virus.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Beuhler|first=Arthur F.|year=2011|title=ISLAMOPHOBIA: A PROJECTION OF THE WEST'S 'DARK SIDE'|volume=2|issue=4|pages=639\u2013653, 765\u2013766|id={{ProQuest|1315158997}}}}</ref> Regardless, negative media images of Muslims in the 1980s and 1990s were compounded by reporting on Islam and Muslims that relied on [[Samuel P. Huntington|Samuel Huntington]]'s 1993 idea of a \"clash of civilizations\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foreignaffairs.com/articles/united-states/1993-06-01/clash-civilizations|title=The Clash of Civilizations?|first1=Samuel P.|last1=Huntington|first2=Samuel P.|last2=Huntington|date=1 June 1993|publisher=|issue=Summer 1993|via=www.foreignaffairs.com}}</ref> for their framework; one that \"the American media were all too ready to embrace after the fall of Communism in the late 1990s.\"<ref name=Ogan>{{cite journal|last1=Ogan|first1=Christine|title=The rise of anti-Muslim prejudice: Media and Islamophobia in Europe and the United States|journal=International Communication Gazette|date=February 2014|volume=76|issue=1|pages=27\u201343|doi=10.1177/1748048513504048}}</ref>\n\n== Islamophobia in the media==\nAccording to [[Nathan Lean]], editor-in-chief of [[Aslan Media]] and a researcher at [[Georgetown University]], the media plays a major role in promoting Islamophobia across the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arabnews.com/news/451770|title=Media blamed for promoting Islamophobia|work=arabnews.com}}</ref>  According to Elizabeth Poole in the ''Encyclopedia of Race and Ethnic Studies'', the media has been criticized for perpetrating Islamophobia. She cites a case study examining a sample of articles in the British press from between 1994 and 2004, which concluded that Muslim viewpoints were underrepresented and that issues involving Muslims usually depicted them in a negative light. Such portrayals, according to Poole, include the depiction of Islam and Muslims as a threat to Western security and values.<ref>Poole, E. (2003) p. 217</ref> Benn and Jawad write that hostility towards Islam and Muslims are \"closely linked to media portrayals of Islam as barbaric, irrational, primitive and sexist.\"<ref name=\"Brill165\">Benn; Jawad (2004) p. 165</ref>\n\nThere have been various instances in the media about how the Muslim community are often misrepresented to society, mostly in a way that centers heavily on terrorism, and paints Islam with a very broad brush.{{Original research inline|date=May 2017}} This is something that is seen in two major magazines, ''[[Newsweek]]'' and ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', which have been covering relations between the U.S. and Afghanistan over the last decade. Both of these publications distributed twenty leading articles that depicted about 57% of negative coverage in regards to current events in Afghanistan, about 37% neutral coverage, and only around 6% was positive information.<ref name=Shabir>{{Cite journal|last=Shabir|first=Ghulam|last2=Ali|first2=Shahzad|last3=Iqbal|first3=Zafar|year=2011|title=US Mass Media and Image of Afghanistan: Portrayal of Afghanistan by Newsweek and Time|journal=South Asian Studies|volume=26|issue=1|pages=83\u2013101|id={{ProQuest|1315320667}}}}</ref> This negative content would often consist of excessive mentioning of Al-Qaida and the Taliban, mistreatment of women, the recruitment of terrorists, etc.<ref name=Shabir /> These are in fact very real occurrences that are present in this part of the world, but primarily focusing on activities of radical groups could lead others to develop a one sided view of Islam.{{Original research inline|date=May 2017}}\n\nIn 2018, [[The Washington Post]] completed a study to examine newspapers\u2019 coverage of Muslims compared to Catholics, Jews, and Hindus.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bleich |first1=Erik |last2=van der Veen |first2=Maurits |title=Media portrayals of Muslims: a comparative sentiment analysis of American newspapers, 1996\u20132015 |journal=Journal of the Western Political Science Association |pages=1\u201320 |date=2018 |doi=10.1080/21565503.2018.1531770 }}</ref> The study first established a baseline for neutrality by analyzing 48,000 newspapers from various US newspapers between 1996 and 2015. <ref name=Bleich>{{cite news |last1=Bleich |first1=Erik |last2=van der Veen |first2=Maurits\u00a0|date=2018-12-20 |title=Newspaper coverage of Muslims is negative. And it's not because of terrorism. |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/monkey-cage/wp/2018/12/20/newspaper-coverage-of-muslims-is-negative-and-its-not-because-of-terrorism/#comments-wrapper |work=The Washington Post |location=United States |access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref> Next the study analyzed 850,000 articles of which about 28% mentioned \u201cMuslim\u201d or \u201cIslam\u201d, about 41% that mentioned \u201cCatholic\u201d, about 29% that mentioned \u201cJew\u201d, and about 2% that mentioned \u201cHindu\u201d.<ref name=Bleich /> This study found that 78% of all the articles that mentioned \u201cMuslim\u201d or \u201cIslam\u201d were negative in comparison \u201dwith only 40 percent of those about Catholics, 46 percent about Jews, and 49 percent about Hindus.\u201d<ref name=Bleich /> The study further filtered the content by cross referencing with articles that included \u201cterrorism,\u201d \u201cextremism,\u201d \u201cradicalism,\u201d \u201cfundamentalism,\u201d or \u201cfanaticism,\u201d \u201cor their variants\u201d.<ref name=Bleich /> This revealed articles that contain terrorism and extremism words are more negative than those that do not.<ref name=Bleich /> However, 69% of articles that do not contain references to terrorism and extremism were still negative.<ref name=Bleich /> When the study removed articles with a mention of a foreign country \u201c54 percent are negative, compared with only 37 percent of articles about Catholics, 36 percent of articles about Jews, and only 29 percent of articles about Hindus under similar conditions\u201d.<ref name=Bleich />\n\nBritish scholars Egorova and Tudor cite European researchers in suggesting that expressions used in the media such as \"Islamic terrorism\", \"Islamic bombs\" and \"violent Islam\" while not using the same terms relating to non-Muslims have resulted in a negative perception of Islam.<ref>See Egorova; Tudor (2003) pp. 2\u20133, which cites the conclusions of Marquina and Rebolledo in: \"A. Marquina, V. G. Rebolledo, 'The Dialogue between the European Union and the Islamic World' in Interreligious Dialogues: Christians, Jews, Muslims, Annals of the European Academy of Sciences and Arts, v. 24, no. 10, Austria, 2000, pp. 166\u20138. \"</ref>\n\nThere have also been examples in the film industry in which Muslims are often associated with terrorism, such as in the 1998 movie ''[[The Siege (1998 film)|The Siege]]''.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wilkins|first=Karin|last2=Downing|first2=John|year=2002|title=Mediating terrorism: Text and protest in interpretations of The Siege|journal=Critical Studies in Media Communication|volume=19|issue=4|pages=419\u2013437|id={{ProQuest|220400043}}|doi=10.1080/07393180216571}}</ref> Some critics of this movie have stated that the manner in which Islam is portrayed in this film only furthers the stereotype that Muslims in are correlated with terrorism and savagery.{{Original research inline|date=May 2017}}\n\n===United States===\nIn 2011, the [[Center for American Progress]] published ''Fear, Inc.: The Roots of the Islamophobia Network in America''.<ref>[http://www.americanprogress.org/issues/religion/report/2011/08/26/10165/fear-inc/ \"Fear, Inc.: The Roots of the Islamophobia Network in America\"].</ref> The goal of the report was to expose the organizations, scholars, pundits and activists that comprised a network dedicated to the spread of misinformation and propaganda about American Muslims and Islam.<ref name=Duss />\n:The report found that seven charitable foundations spent $42.6 million between 2001 and 2009 to support the spread of anti-Muslim rhetoric. The efforts of a small cadre of funders and misinformation experts were amplified by an echo chamber of the religious right, conservative media, grassroots organizations, and politicians who sought to introduce a fringe perspective on American Muslims into the public discourse.<ref name=Duss>{{cite journal|last1=Duss|first1=Matthew|title=Fear, Inc. 2.0 \u2013 The Islamophobia Network's Efforts to Manufacture Hate in America|journal=Center for American Progress|date=February 2015|pages=1\u201387|url=https://cdn.americanprogress.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/FearInc-report2.11.pdf}}</ref>\nA 2010 Gallup poll has even revealed that about 43% of Americans reported feeling some type of prejudice against Muslims, while the religious group itself makes up one of the smallest populations in the entire country.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bowe|first=Brian|last2=Fahmy|first2=Shahira|last3=Matthes|first3=Jorg|year=2015|title=U.S. Newspapers Provide Nuanced Picture of Islam|journal=Newspaper Research Journal|volume=36|issue=1|pages=42\u201357|id={{ProQuest|1695761054}}|doi=10.1177/073953291503600104}}</ref> This indicates that individuals have developed strong opinions about this group of people based on what has been heavily displayed by the media, which has often shown to be negative information.\n\nA report from the [[University of California Berkeley]] and the [[Council on American\u2013Islamic Relations]] estimated that {{US$|206 million|long=no}} was funded to 33 groups whose primary purpose was \"to promote prejudice against, or hatred of, Islam and Muslims\" in the United States between 2008 and 2013, with a total of 74 groups contributing to Islamophobia in the United States during that period.<ref>{{cite news |title=Funding fear of Muslims: $206m went to promoting 'hatred', report finds |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2016/jun/20/islamophobia-funding-cair-berkeley-report |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=June 20, 2016 |language=en}}</ref> This has been referred to as the \"Islamophobia industry\" by scholars Nathan Lean and [[John Esposito]].<ref>{{Cite book|title = The Islamophobia Industry: How the Right Manufactures Fear of Muslims|last = Lean|first = Nathan|publisher = Pluto Press|year = 2012|isbn = |location = |page = 66}}</ref>\n\n==== Fox News ====\nIn 2014, [[Vox Media]] editor [[Max Fisher]] said that [[Fox News]] is only a small component of the Islamophobia on U.S media.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2014/10/8/6918485/the-overt-islamophobia-on-american-tv-news-is-out-of-control|title=It's not just Fox News: Islamophobia on cable news is out of control|last=Fisher|first=Max|date=January 13, 2015|work=Vox}}</ref>\n[[File:Gathering of eagles.jpg|thumb|An American protester self-identifying as Islamophobic.]] Fox News has also had to retract false claims about Muslims.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/19/world/europe/fox-news-apologizes-for-false-claims-of-muslim-only-areas-in-england-and-france.html|title=Fox News Apologizes for False Claims of Muslim-Only Areas in England and France|last=Mackey|first=Robert|date=January 19, 2015|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> In 2009, Dr [[Fred Vultee]] released an analysis<ref name=Vultee>{{cite journal|last1=Vultee|first1=Fred|title=Jump Back Jack, Mohammed's Here|journal=Journalism Studies|date=October 2009|volume=10|issue=5|pages=623\u2013638|doi=10.1080/14616700902797333}}</ref> of [[Fox News]] which sought to explore the media outlet's practices through the prism of [[Edward Said]]'s concept of [[Orientalism (book)|Orientalism]]; the practices \"create an ideological clearinghouse for a uniquely menacing image of Islam.\" This image is one of a rational, progressive West at constant and irreconcilable odds with an irrational, backward East. In his study, Vultee asserts, \"The discourse Fox creates with its audience helps to set a foundation for polarized commentary and to legitimize support for a limitless war on the unknown.\" As part of his investigation, Vultee analyzed the contents of foxnews.com from 2007 to 2009. According to his research:\n:A visit any day to the website of the Fox News Channel is likely to offer yet another piece of a sinister puzzle: the looming threat of Islam to everything the West holds dear. There is an armed threat, of course, in Afghanistan and Iraq and possibly as near as the shopping mall. But there is also a cultural danger that menaces all of Europe, that stalks coffee shops and classrooms, that endangers individual children and entire health-care systems with its irreducible demands, that hates Barbie and Valentine's Day and even the Three Little Pigs. And even as the West watches, ''they'' have overtaken ''us'' as the world's largest religion.<ref name=Vultee />\n\nFox News does not necessarily create the pieces of this puzzle. Much of their content and coverage comes from the [[Associated Press]] or is attributed to one of the newspapers belonging to the British arm of [[Rupert Murdoch]]'s [[News Corp (2013\u2013present)|News Corp]]\u2014''[[The Times]]'', ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' and ''[[The Sunday Times]]''. \"What Fox does is act as a collator\u2014a clearinghouse of unrelated and often quite unremarkable developments that, taken together, create a clear ideological dialogue with its audience about how to relate to and interpret the Islamic  world.\"<ref name=Vultee />\n\nIn the February 2014 issue of the ''[[International Communication Gazette]]'', Dr [[Christine Ogan]] and her colleagues published an article, \"The rise of anti-Muslim prejudice: Media and Islamophobia in Europe and the United States.\"<ref name=Ogan /> In their analysis of various polling data, the researchers note:\n:Empirical evidence for such a possible interaction between media coverage and latent anti-Muslim feelings is mounting. One study that analyzed Fox News viewers' anti-Muslim feelings reported, for example, that 60% of Republicans who most trusted Fox News also believe that Muslims were attempting to establish Sharia law in the United States. And as we reported earlier, those trusting Fox News the most also tend to believe that Islamic values are incompatible with American values (68%). That percentage is lower for those who most trust CNN (37%) or public television/new [media] (37%).\nThe researchers further claimed that:\n:Since media coverage of Muslims and Islam is likely to shape the opinions of those who have limited or no contact with this religion and its people, it is important to analyze the potential associations these media portrayals might have with people's attitudes toward Islam in general and Muslims in particular.\n\n===Europe===\nA 2012 study indicates that Muslims across different European countries, such as France, Germany and the United Kingdom, experience the highest degree of Islamophobia in the media.<ref name=kunst2012b>{{cite journal | last1 = Kunst | last2 = Sam | last3 = Ulleberg | year = 2013| title = Perceived islamophobia: Scale development and validation | doi = 10.1016/j.ijintrel.2012.11.001 | journal = International Journal of Intercultural Relations | volume =  37| issue = 2| pages =  225\u2013237| url = https://zenodo.org/record/812038}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, the [[European Network Against Racism|ENAR]] (European Network Against Racism) conducted research and found that Muslim women are often portrayed as a suppressed group by the media. According to the reports, wearing a hijab, or any religious clothing is depicted as a form of the violation of women\u2019s rights by news agencies which puts Islam as a religion under a negative light.<ref name=\":0\">\u201cForgotten Women: The Impact of Islamophobia on Muslim Women .\u201d Forgotten Women: The Impact of Islamophobia on Muslim Women . European network against racism . Accessed November 6, 2019. <nowiki>https://www.enar-eu.org/IMG/pdf/factsheet9-european_lr_1_.pdf</nowiki>.</ref> Through social media platforms such as Facebook and Twitter, Muslim women are often targets of abuse, sexist insults and hate speeches. According to the reports, in 2015, 90% of the victims of Islamophobic incidents in Netherlands that were reported to Meld Islamophobia were Muslim women.<ref name=\":0\" /> The report also mentions that 64% of the British public receives information about Islam through mass media which may explain why the public displays feelings of hostility towards the Muslim Community, particularly the women.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAccording to the \"European Islamophobia Report 2018,\" released by the Foundation for Political, Economic and Social Research ([https://www.setav.org/en/ SETA]) in the [[Anadolu Agency]] newsletter, news media coverage in Europe, have minimal news that favour Muslim Groups.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/turkey/anti-muslim-racism-in-europe-on-rise-in-2018-report/1597957|title=Anti-Muslim racism in Europe on rise in 2018: Report|website=www.aa.com.tr|access-date=2019-11-08}}</ref> According to research carried out by the City University in London, only 0.5% of journalists in the UK are Muslim, and thus the underrepresentation of Muslim Journalists could be a crucial reason behind the lack of positive news coverage with regards to Muslim Communities.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/voices/why-the-british-media-is-responsible-for-the-rise-in-islamophobia-in-britain-a6967546.html|title=Why the British media is responsible for the rise in Islamophobia in Britain|date=2016-04-04|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-11-08}}</ref> Moreover, the report also mentioned that the Islamophobic language used in hate speeches by politicians could also impact the representation of Muslims in the minds of the Europeans.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nAn article by Jan Kovar in the UNYP Newsletter (University of New York in Prague), states that during the course of the migration crisis in Europe (2013-2016), Muslim migrants were portrayed as a security threat to the country in 77% and 67% of news stories by agencies in Czech and Slovak respectively, due to which their community experienced antagonism.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unyp.cz/news/islamophobia-europe-media-blame|title=Islamophobia in Europe: is the media to blame?|date=2018-11-27|website=University of New York in Prague|language=en|access-date=2019-11-08}}</ref>\n\nMiqdaad Versi of \u2018[[The Independent]]\u2019 filed a complaint when the \u2018[[Daily Star (United Kingdom)|Daily Star]]\u2019, published a headline stating, \u201cUK mosques fundraising for terror\u201d as it was misleading for the public. Following this, the newspaper clarified its error claiming that the UK mosques were actually \u201cnot involved in any way\u201d.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n===United Kingdom===\nIn 2008, [[Peter Oborne]] of ''[[The Independent]]'' wrote that British tabloids such as [[The Sun (United Kingdom)|''The Sun'']] tend to highlight crimes committed by Muslims in an undue and disproportionate manner.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/the-shameful-islamophobia-at-the-heart-of-britains-press-861096.html|title=The shameful Islamophobia at the heart of Britain's press|work=The Independent}}</ref> In 2013, British Muslim historian [[Humayun Ansari]] said that politicians and the media are still fuelling Islamophobia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/opinion/2013/07/201374135331488994.html|title=Islamophobia rises in British society|first=Humayun|last=Ansari|date=July 8, 2013|work=aljazeera.com}}</ref>\n\n[[John E. Richardson]]'s 2004 book ''(Mis)representing Islam: the racism and rhetoric of British broadsheet newspapers'', criticized the [[Media of the United Kingdom|British media]] for propagating negative [[Stereotypes of Arabs and Muslims|stereotypes of Muslims]] and fueling anti-Muslim prejudice.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Richardson|first=John E.|title=(Mis)representing Islam: the racism and rhetoric of British broadsheet newspapers|publisher=[[John Benjamins Publishing Company]]|year=2004|isbn=90-272-2699-7|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WanqiF2XULsC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=}}</ref> In another study conducted by John E. Richardson, he found that 85% of mainstream newspaper articles treated Muslims as a [[Muslims in British media|homogeneous mass]] who were imagined as a threat to British society.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Richardson | first1 = J. E. | year = 2009 | title = 'Get Shot of the Lot of Them': Election Reporting of Muslims in British Newspapers | url = | journal = Patterns of Prejudice | volume = 43 | issue = 3\u20134| pages = 355\u2013377 | doi=10.1080/00313220903109276}}</ref>\n\n==Social media==\nAccording to ''The Social Network of Hate: Inside Facebook's Walls of Islamophobia'', by British academic Imran Awan, Awan himself had went through 100 different Facebook pages online in which he found \"494 specific instances of online hate speech directed against Muslim communities.\"<ref name=494HateSpeech>{{cite web|url=http://www.middleeasteye.net/columns/social-network-hate-inside-facebooks-walls-islamophobia-1723501542|title=The social network of hate: Inside Facebook's walls of Islamophobia|work= Middle East Eye|first1=Imran |last1=Awan |date=29 July 2016 }}</ref> The five most common forms of abuse were:\n#that Muslim women were a security threat (15%)<ref name=494HateSpeech/>\n#that Muslims should be deported (13%)<ref name=494HateSpeech/>\n#that Muslims were potential terrorists (12%)<ref name=494HateSpeech/>\n#that Muslims were at war with non-Muslims (11%)<ref name=494HateSpeech/>\n#that Muslims were rapists (9%)<ref name=494HateSpeech/>\n\nIn 2016 in Europe, Facebook had created a new code of conduct that specified to decrease the hateful speech being used on the website.<ref name=\"European Commission\">{{cite web|url=http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_IP-16-1937_en.htm|title=European Commission - PRESS RELEASES - Press release - European Commission and IT Companies announce Code of Conduct on illegal online hate speech|website=europa.eu}}</ref> The head leader of public policy in Europe operating Twitter, Karen White, stated that \"Hateful conduct has no place on Twitter and we will continue to tackle this issue head on alongside our partners in industry and civil society. We remain committed to letting the tweets flow. However, there is a clear distinction between freedom of expression and conduct that incites violence and hate.\"<ref name=\"European Commission\"/>\n\n== Lack of representation ==\nSome have noted that few Muslims are represented in the media when discussing policies that affect Muslims directly. In 2017, journalists at ''Media Matters'' compiled a list of guests that were invited onto three US cable news shows ([[CNN]], [[Fox News]], [[MSNBC]]) in the week from January 30 to February 5 to discuss President Trump's controversial [[Executive Order 13769]], which would ban immigration from seven Muslim-majority countries. They found that of the 176 guests that were invited to discuss the issue, less than 8% were Muslim.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mediamatters.org/blog/2017/02/09/when-discussing-trumps-muslim-ban-cable-news-excluded-muslims/215284|title=When Discussing Trump's Muslim Ban, Cable News Excluded Muslims|last=Mast|first=Nina|date=9 February 2017|work=Media Matters for America|access-date=25 April 2017|last2=Alderman|first2=Julie}}</ref> In 2014, Palestinian activists noted a similar pattern with the underrepresentation of Palestinian guests on cable news during the [[2014 Israel\u2013Gaza conflict|2014 Israeli\u2013Gaza conflict]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/opinion/2014/08/why-are-palestinian-voices-exc-2014818111423499809.html|title=Why are Palestinian voices excluded?|last=Sabawi|first=Samah|date=21 August 2014|website=Al Jazeera English|access-date=25 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nA December 2015 survey by [[City, University of London]] of journalists found an underrepresentation of Muslims in the field in the UK. Only 0.4% of British journalists identified as Muslim or Hindu, 31.6% were Christian, and 61.1% had \"no religion.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/03/uk-poor-reporting-media-illiteracy-fuel-islamophobia-160329161759712.html|title=UK: Poor reporting, media illiteracy fuel Islamophobia|website=Al Jazeera English|access-date=2017-04-26}}</ref>\n\n== Disproportionate coverage ==\nIn 2009, [[Mehdi Hasan]] in the ''[[New Statesman]]'' criticized Western media for over-reporting a few [[Islamist terrorist]] incidents but under-reporting the much larger number of planned non-Islamist terrorist attacks carried out by \"non-Irish [[White people|white]] folks\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Know your enemy|author=Mehdi Hasan|work=[[New Statesman]]|date=9 July 2009|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/2009/07/mehdi-hasan-muslim-terrorism-white-british|accessdate=2010-04-09}}</ref>  A 2017 study by students at [[Georgia State University]] concluded that \"controlling for target type, fatalities, and being arrested, attacks by Muslim perpetrators received, on average, 449% more coverage than other attacks.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kearns|first=Erin M.|last2=Betus|first2=Allison|last3=Lemieux|first3=Anthony|date=5 March 2017|title=Why Do Some Terrorist Attacks Receive More Media Attention Than Others?|ssrn=2928138|journal=|volume=|pages=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Media personalities ==\nSome media personalities are associated with maintaining Islamophobic perspectives.\n\nThe obituary in ''[[The Guardian]]'' for the Italian journalist [[Oriana Fallaci]] described her as \"notorious for her Islamaphobia\" [sic].<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/italy/story/0,,1873911,00.html Obituary of Oriana Fallaci] \u2013 [[The Guardian]], 16 September 2006. \"''Controversial Italian journalist famed for her interviews and war reports but notorious for her Islamaphobia''\"</ref>\n\n== Arabophobia ==\nAfter the [[September 11 attacks|events of September 11]], coordinated by the [[Islamic terrorist]] organization [[Al-Qaeda]], the media's interest in Islam and the Muslim community has been significant but considered deeply problematic by some. Within minutes of planes crashing into the Twin Towers in New York, \"Muslim\" and \"terrorism\" had become inseparable. Many scholars{{Which|date=November 2019}} felt that the events of September 11 brought to the fore a marked tone of hysteria, frenzied and ill-informed reporting and a general decline in journalistic standards as far as discussions about Islam and Muslim were concerned.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite journal|last1=Ahmad|first1=Fauzia|title=British Muslim Perceptions and Opinions on News Coverage of September 11|journal=Journal of Ethnic and Migration Studies|date=August 2006|volume=32|issue=6|pages=961\u2013982|doi=10.1080/13691830600761479}}</ref>\n\nThe fear of Muslims has become more intensified ever since the attacks. The media portrays Islams as a race of people directly associated with violence. In public discussions and in the media, Muslims are mostly portrayed as a monolithic bloc, a closed and united group of people who are totally different from or even intimidating and hostile to a likewise closed \"West,\" which is Christian, secular, liberal, and democratic. The description of the Muslims and Western worlds as two contrasting and contradictory poles leads to a dualistic understanding of relations, disregarding many fine distinctions and exceptions. The so called risk of Arabs has been hyped throughout by the media channels to an extent that now Westerners see Muslims only in the context of somebody who is an adversary of the democratic world order and modernization.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\" />\n\n=== Arabophobia stats ===\nWhen Muslims and Islam are discussed on news networks, it is often regarding the \"[[War on Terror]].\"<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Pervez|first1=Sadia|title=Portrayal of Arabs and Islam in the talk shows of CNN & Fox News|journal=Journal of Media Studies|date=July 2010|volume=25|issue=2|pages=122\u2013140}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#ddd;\"\n| colspan=\"6\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''Depiction of Arabs on U.S. News channels'''\n|-\n! Issues !! Fox News !! Special Report !! Larry King Live !! Late Edition !! Total\n|-\n| Art & Culture || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| Crisis (Socio-eco) || 4 || 19 || 3 || 4 || 30\n|-\n| Development || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| Human Rights || 0 || 1 || 0 || 0 || 1\n|-\n| International Relations || 0 || 1 || 0 || 0 || 1\n|-\n| Religion || 0 || 3 || 2 || 0 || 5\n|-\n| Politics || 6 || 9 || 5 || 12 || 32\n|-\n| War on Terror || 13 || 10 || 14 || 13 || 50\n|-\n| Total || 23 || 43 || 24 || 29 || 119\n|}\n\n== Response ==\nSome media outlets are working explicitly against Islamophobia, and sometimes, the government is accused of conspiring.<ref>{{cite news|last1=German|first1=Lindsey|title='Blame the Muslims': Islamophobia is fuelled by government and media|url=http://www.middleeasteye.net/columns/blame-muslims-islamophobia-fuelled-government-and-media-877365179|agency=Middle East Eye|date=Feb 11, 2015}}</ref> In 2008, [[Fairness and Accuracy in Reporting]] (\"FAIR\") published a study \"Smearcasting, How Islamophobes Spread Bigotry, Fear and Misinformation.\" The report cites several instances where mainstream or close to mainstream journalists, authors, and academics have made analyses that essentialize negative traits as an inherent part of Muslims' moral makeup.<ref>Steve Rendall and Isabel Macdonald, [http://fair.org/extra-online-articles/making-islamophobia-mainstream/ Making Islamophobia Mainstream; How Muslim-bashers broadcast their bigotry], summary of [[Fairness and Accuracy in Reporting]] report, at its website, November/December 2008.</ref> FAIR also established the \"[[Forum Against Islamophobia and Racism]]\", designed to monitor coverage in the media and establish dialogue with media organizations. Following the [[September 11 attacks|attacks of September 11, 2001]], the [[Islamic Society of Britain]]'s \"Islam Awareness Week\" and the \"Best of British Islam Festival\" were introduced to improve community relations and raise awareness about Islam.<ref>Encyclopedia of Race and Ethnic studies, p. 218</ref> In 2012, the [[Organisation of Islamic Cooperation]] stated that they will launch a TV channel to counter  Islamophobia.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/411340 | title=OIC will launch channel to counter Islamophobia | date=April 19, 2012 | agency=Arab News | accessdate=January 9, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n== Pushback ==\nTwo days after completing his short book: ''Lettre aux escrocs de l'islamophobie qui font le jeu des racistes (Letter to the Islamophobia Frauds Who Play into the Hands of Racists)'', [[Charb|St\u00e9phane \"Charb\" Charbonnier]], editor of [[Charlie Hebdo]], was dead. Charb and 11 others were murdered on January 7, 2015 by [[Charlie Hebdo shooting#Ch\u00e9rif and Sa\u00efd Kouachi|Ch\u00e9rif and Said Kouachi]] in their [[Charlie Hebdo shooting|attack on the Parisian office]] of the satirical magazine.\n\nDuring his time as editor, Charlie Hebdo aimed its satire at Catholicism, Judaism and radical Islam in equal measure. In his final, posthumous missive, Charb rejects all accusations that he ran a \"racist\" or \"Islamophobic\" magazine. \"He argues\u2014from a left-wing, anti-racist, militantly secular viewpoint\u2014that the word \"Islamophobia\" is a trap, set by an unholy alliance of Muslim radicals and the unthinking, liberal Western media. The real issue, he says, is racism and Charlie Hebdo was never racist...\"<ref name=Independent>{{cite news|title=Charlie Hebdo editor's final book: 'Letter to the Islamophobia Frauds Who Play into the Hands of Racists'|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/charlie-hebdo-editors-final-book-letter-to-the-islamophobia-frauds-who-play-into-the-hands-of-racists-10193565.html|agency=The Independent (London)|publisher=Independent Digital News and Media Ltd.|date=April 22, 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:2011-11-02 Incendie \u00e0 Charlie Hebdo - Charb - 06.jpg|thumb|Charb on November 2, 2011]]\n:Really, the word \"Islamophobia\" is badly chosen if it's supposed to described the hatred which some lame-brains have for Muslims. And it is not only badly chosen, it is dangerous. From a purely etymological viewpoint, Islamophobia ought to mean \"fear of Islam\"\u2014yet the inventors, promoters and users of this word deploy it to denounce hatred of Muslims. But isn't it odd that \"Muslimophobia,\" or just \"racism,\" isn't used instead of \"Islamophobia.\"\n\n:...\n\n:Racist language\u2014which pressure groups, politicians and intellectuals had managed to corral in the space between the mouth of the xenophobe and his kitchen door\u2014has escaped into the street. It flows through the media and sullies the networks of social media.\n\n:So, yes, we are in the middle of an explosion of racist behavior\u2014yet the word \"racism\" is used only timidly, and is on the way to being supplanted by \"Islamophobia.\" And the campaigners for multiculturalism, who try to foist the notion of \"Islamophobia\" on the judicial and political authorities, have only one aim in mind: to force the victims of racism into identifying themselves as Muslims.\n\n:The fact that racists are also Islamophobic is, I'm afraid, irrelevant. They are, first and foremost, racists. By attacking Islam, they are targeting foreigners or people of foreign origin. But by focusing only on their Islamophobia, we are minimizing the danger of racism. The anti-racist campaigners of old are in danger of becoming overspecialized niche retailers in a minority form of discrimination.\n\n:...\n\n:However, why do the cartoonists of Charlie Hebdo, who know that their drawings will be exploited by the media, by the retailers of anti-Islamophobia, by far-right Muslims and nationalists, insist on drawing Mohamed and other \"sacred\" symbols of Islam? Simply because the Charlie Hebdo drawings do not have the vast majority of Muslims as their target. We believe that Muslims are capable of recognising a tongue-in-cheek.<ref name=Charb>{{cite book|last1=Charb|last2=Translated by John Lichfield|title=Lettre aux escrocs de l'islamophobie qui font le jeu des racistes (Letter to the Islamophobia Frauds Who Play into the Hands of Racists)|date=April 16, 2015|publisher=French and European Publications Inc.|location=France|isbn=978-2357660861|pages=1\u201396|edition=First}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Islamophobia]]\n** [[Islamophobia in Australia]]\n** [[Islamophobia in Canada]]\n** [[Islamophobia in Norway]]\n** [[Islamophobia in Sweden]]\n** [[Islamophobia in the United Kingdom]]\n** [[Islamophobia in the United States]]\n** [[Islamophobia in India]]\n** [[Islamophobia Watch]]\n* [[List of critics of Islam]]\n* [[Xenophobia]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Media bias]]\n[[Category:Islamophobia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Islamophobia}}\n'''Islamophobia in the media''' refers to the occurrence or perception that media outlets tend to cover Muslims or Islam-related topics in a negative light. [[Islamophobia]] is defined as \"Intense dislike or fear of [[Islam]], esp. as a political force; hostility or prejudice towards [[Muslims]]\".<ref name=OED>{{cite web|url=http://www.oed.com/view/Entry/248449?|publisher=Oxford University Press|title=Oxford English Dictionary: Islamophobia}}{{paywall}}</ref><ref>See also:\n* {{cite web|title=Islamophobia|url=https://en.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/islamophobia|website=en.oxforddictionaries.com|accessdate=10 November 2016}}\n* {{cite web|title=Islamophobia|url=http://www.dictionary.com/browse/islamophobia|website=dictionary.com|accessdate=10 November 2016}}\n* {{cite web|title=Islamophobia|url=http://www.collinsdictionary.com/dictionary/english/islamophobia|website=collinsdictionary.com}}</ref>\n\n== Historical context ==\nSome researchers point to the [[Iranian Revolution]] in 1979 as a starting point for Islamophobia in the United States. It may be due to the growing influence of [[Islamism|political Islam]] around the same period. In his book, ''The Modern Middle East'', author Mehran Kamrava notes that the \"rise in the popularity and spread of political Islam can be traced to the 1980s and even earlier, when a general trend in the politicization of Islam began sweeping across the Middle East following the Arab 'victory' in the [[Yom Kippur War|1973 War]] and the success of the Iranian revolution.\"<ref name=Kamrava>{{cite book|last1=Kamrava|first1=Mehran|title=The Modern Middle East|date=2013|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley, California|isbn=978-0-520-27781-6|page=314|edition=Third}}</ref> Others find Islamophobia present in the United States far earlier and argue that Americans were using the fear of Islam as a unifying concept in defining America. Some also believe that the phenomenon of Islamophobia is a psychological defense mechanism, which is spreading through mass media like a virus.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Beuhler|first=Arthur F.|year=2011|title=ISLAMOPHOBIA: A PROJECTION OF THE WEST'S 'DARK SIDE'|volume=2|issue=4|pages=639\u2013653, 765\u2013766|id={{ProQuest|1315158997}}}}</ref> Regardless, negative media images of Muslims in the 1980s and 1990s were compounded by reporting on Islam and Muslims that relied on [[Samuel P. Huntington|Samuel Huntington]]'s 1993 idea of a \"clash of civilizations\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foreignaffairs.com/articles/united-states/1993-06-01/clash-civilizations|title=The Clash of Civilizations?|first1=Samuel P.|last1=Huntington|first2=Samuel P.|last2=Huntington|date=1 June 1993|publisher=|issue=Summer 1993|via=www.foreignaffairs.com}}</ref> for their framework; one that \"the American media were all too ready to embrace after the fall of Communism in the late 1990s.\"<ref name=Ogan>{{cite journal|last1=Ogan|first1=Christine|title=The rise of anti-Muslim prejudice: Media and Islamophobia in Europe and the United States|journal=International Communication Gazette|date=February 2014|volume=76|issue=1|pages=27\u201343|doi=10.1177/1748048513504048}}</ref>\n\n== Islamophobia in the media==\nAccording to [[Nathan Lean]], editor-in-chief of [[Aslan Media]] and a researcher at [[Georgetown University]], the media plays a major role in promoting Islamophobia across the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arabnews.com/news/451770|title=Media blamed for promoting Islamophobia|work=arabnews.com}}</ref>  According to Elizabeth Poole in the ''Encyclopedia of Race and Ethnic Studies'', the media has been criticized for perpetrating Islamophobia. She cites a case study examining a sample of articles in the British press from between 1994 and 2004, which concluded that Muslim viewpoints were underrepresented and that issues involving Muslims usually depicted them in a negative light. Such portrayals, according to Poole, include the depiction of Islam and Muslims as a threat to Western security and values.<ref>Poole, E. (2003) p. 217</ref> Benn and Jawad write that hostility towards Islam and Muslims are \"closely linked to media portrayals of Islam as barbaric, irrational, primitive and sexist.\"<ref name=\"Brill165\">Benn; Jawad (2004) p. 165</ref>\n\nThere have been various instances in the media about how the Muslim community are often misrepresented to society, mostly in a way that centers heavily on terrorism, and paints Islam with a very broad brush.{{Original research inline|date=May 2017}} This is something that is seen in two major magazines, ''[[Newsweek]]'' and ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', which have been covering relations between the U.S. and Afghanistan over the last decade. Both of these publications distributed twenty leading articles that depicted about 57% of negative coverage in regards to current events in Afghanistan, about 37% neutral coverage, and only around 6% was positive information.<ref name=Shabir>{{Cite journal|last=Shabir|first=Ghulam|last2=Ali|first2=Shahzad|last3=Iqbal|first3=Zafar|year=2011|title=US Mass Media and Image of Afghanistan: Portrayal of Afghanistan by Newsweek and Time|journal=South Asian Studies|volume=26|issue=1|pages=83\u2013101|id={{ProQuest|1315320667}}}}</ref> This negative content would often consist of excessive mentioning of Al-Qaida and the Taliban, mistreatment of women, the recruitment of terrorists, etc.<ref name=Shabir /> These are in fact very real occurrences that are present in this part of the world, but primarily focusing on activities of radical groups could lead others to develop a one sided view of Islam.{{Original research inline|date=May 2017}}\n\nIn 2018, [[The Washington Post]] completed a study to examine newspapers\u2019 coverage of Muslims compared to Catholics, Jews, and Hindus.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bleich |first1=Erik |last2=van der Veen |first2=Maurits |title=Media portrayals of Muslims: a comparative sentiment analysis of American newspapers, 1996\u20132015 |journal=Journal of the Western Political Science Association |pages=1\u201320 |date=2018 |doi=10.1080/21565503.2018.1531770 }}</ref> The study first established a baseline for neutrality by analyzing 48,000 newspapers from various US newspapers between 1996 and 2015. <ref name=Bleich>{{cite news |last1=Bleich |first1=Erik |last2=van der Veen |first2=Maurits\u00a0|date=2018-12-20 |title=Newspaper coverage of Muslims is negative. And it's not because of terrorism. |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/monkey-cage/wp/2018/12/20/newspaper-coverage-of-muslims-is-negative-and-its-not-because-of-terrorism/#comments-wrapper |work=The Washington Post |location=United States |access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref> Next the study analyzed 850,000 articles of which about 28% mentioned \u201cMuslim\u201d or \u201cIslam\u201d, about 41% that mentioned \u201cCatholic\u201d, about 29% that mentioned \u201cJew\u201d, and about 2% that mentioned \u201cHindu\u201d.<ref name=Bleich /> This study found that 78% of all the articles that mentioned \u201cMuslim\u201d or \u201cIslam\u201d were negative in comparison \u201dwith only 40 percent of those about Catholics, 46 percent about Jews, and 49 percent about Hindus.\u201d<ref name=Bleich /> The study further filtered the content by cross referencing with articles that included \u201cterrorism,\u201d \u201cextremism,\u201d \u201cradicalism,\u201d \u201cfundamentalism,\u201d or \u201cfanaticism,\u201d \u201cor their variants\u201d.<ref name=Bleich /> This revealed articles that contain terrorism and extremism words are more negative than those that do not.<ref name=Bleich /> However, 69% of articles that do not contain references to terrorism and extremism were still negative.<ref name=Bleich /> When the study removed articles with a mention of a foreign country \u201c54 percent are negative, compared with only 37 percent of articles about Catholics, 36 percent of articles about Jews, and only 29 percent of articles about Hindus under similar conditions\u201d.<ref name=Bleich />\n\nBritish scholars Egorova and Tudor cite European researchers in suggesting that expressions used in the media such as \"Islamic terrorism\", \"Islamic bombs\" and \"violent Islam\" while not using the same terms relating to non-Muslims have resulted in a negative perception of Islam.<ref>See Egorova; Tudor (2003) pp. 2\u20133, which cites the conclusions of Marquina and Rebolledo in: \"A. Marquina, V. G. Rebolledo, 'The Dialogue between the European Union and the Islamic World' in Interreligious Dialogues: Christians, Jews, Muslims, Annals of the European Academy of Sciences and Arts, v. 24, no. 10, Austria, 2000, pp. 166\u20138. \"</ref>\n\nThere have also been examples in the film industry in which Muslims are often associated with terrorism, such as in the 1998 movie ''[[The Siege (1998 film)|The Siege]]''.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wilkins|first=Karin|last2=Downing|first2=John|year=2002|title=Mediating terrorism: Text and protest in interpretations of The Siege|journal=Critical Studies in Media Communication|volume=19|issue=4|pages=419\u2013437|id={{ProQuest|220400043}}|doi=10.1080/07393180216571}}</ref> Some critics of this movie have stated that the manner in which Islam is portrayed in this film only furthers the stereotype that Muslims in are correlated with terrorism and savagery.{{Original research inline|date=May 2017}}\n\n===United States===\nIn 2011, the [[Center for American Progress]] published ''Fear, Inc.: The Roots of the Islamophobia Network in America''.<ref>[http://www.americanprogress.org/issues/religion/report/2011/08/26/10165/fear-inc/ \"Fear, Inc.: The Roots of the Islamophobia Network in America\"].</ref> The goal of the report was to expose the organizations, scholars, pundits and activists that comprised a network dedicated to the spread of misinformation and propaganda about American Muslims and Islam.<ref name=Duss />\n:The report found that seven charitable foundations spent $42.6 million between 2001 and 2009 to support the spread of anti-Muslim rhetoric. The efforts of a small cadre of funders and misinformation experts were amplified by an echo chamber of the religious right, conservative media, grassroots organizations, and politicians who sought to introduce a fringe perspective on American Muslims into the public discourse.<ref name=Duss>{{cite journal|last1=Duss|first1=Matthew|title=Fear, Inc. 2.0 \u2013 The Islamophobia Network's Efforts to Manufacture Hate in America|journal=Center for American Progress|date=February 2015|pages=1\u201387|url=https://cdn.americanprogress.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/FearInc-report2.11.pdf}}</ref>\nA 2010 Gallup poll has even revealed that about 43% of Americans reported feeling some type of prejudice against Muslims, while the religious group itself makes up one of the smallest populations in the entire country.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bowe|first=Brian|last2=Fahmy|first2=Shahira|last3=Matthes|first3=Jorg|year=2015|title=U.S. Newspapers Provide Nuanced Picture of Islam|journal=Newspaper Research Journal|volume=36|issue=1|pages=42\u201357|id={{ProQuest|1695761054}}|doi=10.1177/073953291503600104}}</ref> This indicates that individuals have developed strong opinions about this group of people based on what has been heavily displayed by the media, which has often shown to be negative information.\n\nA report from the [[University of California Berkeley]] and the [[Council on American\u2013Islamic Relations]] estimated that {{US$|206 million|long=no}} was funded to 33 groups whose primary purpose was \"to promote prejudice against, or hatred of, Islam and Muslims\" in the United States between 2008 and 2013, with a total of 74 groups contributing to Islamophobia in the United States during that period.<ref>{{cite news |title=Funding fear of Muslims: $206m went to promoting 'hatred', report finds |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2016/jun/20/islamophobia-funding-cair-berkeley-report |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=June 20, 2016 |language=en}}</ref> This has been referred to as the \"Islamophobia industry\" by scholars Nathan Lean and [[John Esposito]].<ref>{{Cite book|title = The Islamophobia Industry: How the Right Manufactures Fear of Muslims|last = Lean|first = Nathan|publisher = Pluto Press|year = 2012|isbn = |location = |page = 66}}</ref>\n\n==== Fox News ====\nIn 2014, [[Vox Media]] editor [[Max Fisher]] said that [[Fox News]] is only a small component of the Islamophobia on U.S media.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2014/10/8/6918485/the-overt-islamophobia-on-american-tv-news-is-out-of-control|title=It's not just Fox News: Islamophobia on cable news is out of control|last=Fisher|first=Max|date=January 13, 2015|work=Vox}}</ref>\n[[File:Gathering of eagles.jpg|thumb|An American protester self-identifying as Islamophobic.]] Fox News has also had to retract false claims about Muslims.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/19/world/europe/fox-news-apologizes-for-false-claims-of-muslim-only-areas-in-england-and-france.html|title=Fox News Apologizes for False Claims of Muslim-Only Areas in England and France|last=Mackey|first=Robert|date=January 19, 2015|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> In 2009, Dr [[Fred Vultee]] released an analysis<ref name=Vultee>{{cite journal|last1=Vultee|first1=Fred|title=Jump Back Jack, Mohammed's Here|journal=Journalism Studies|date=October 2009|volume=10|issue=5|pages=623\u2013638|doi=10.1080/14616700902797333}}</ref> of [[Fox News]] which sought to explore the media outlet's practices through the prism of [[Edward Said]]'s concept of [[Orientalism (book)|Orientalism]]; the practices \"create an ideological clearinghouse for a uniquely menacing image of Islam.\" This image is one of a rational, progressive West at constant and irreconcilable odds with an irrational, backward East. In his study, Vultee asserts, \"The discourse Fox creates with its audience helps to set a foundation for polarized commentary and to legitimize support for a limitless war on the unknown.\" As part of his investigation, Vultee analyzed the contents of foxnews.com from 2007 to 2009. According to his research:\n:A visit any day to the website of the Fox News Channel is likely to offer yet another piece of a sinister puzzle: the looming threat of Islam to everything the West holds dear. There is an armed threat, of course, in Afghanistan and Iraq and possibly as near as the shopping mall. But there is also a cultural danger that menaces all of Europe, that stalks coffee shops and classrooms, that endangers individual children and entire health-care systems with its irreducible demands, that hates Barbie and Valentine's Day and even the Three Little Pigs. And even as the West watches, ''they'' have overtaken ''us'' as the world's largest religion.<ref name=Vultee />\n\nFox News does not necessarily create the pieces of this puzzle. Much of their content and coverage comes from the [[Associated Press]] or is attributed to one of the newspapers belonging to the British arm of [[Rupert Murdoch]]'s [[News Corp (2013\u2013present)|News Corp]]\u2014''[[The Times]]'', ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' and ''[[The Sunday Times]]''. \"What Fox does is act as a collator\u2014a clearinghouse of unrelated and often quite unremarkable developments that, taken together, create a clear ideological dialogue with its audience about how to relate to and interpret the Islamic  world.\"<ref name=Vultee />\n\nIn the February 2014 issue of the ''[[International Communication Gazette]]'', Dr [[Christine Ogan]] and her colleagues published an article, \"The rise of anti-Muslim prejudice: Media and Islamophobia in Europe and the United States.\"<ref name=Ogan /> In their analysis of various polling data, the researchers note:\n:Empirical evidence for such a possible interaction between media coverage and latent anti-Muslim feelings is mounting. One study that analyzed Fox News viewers' anti-Muslim feelings reported, for example, that 60% of Republicans who most trusted Fox News also believe that Muslims were attempting to establish Sharia law in the United States. And as we reported earlier, those trusting Fox News the most also tend to believe that Islamic values are incompatible with American values (68%). That percentage is lower for those who most trust CNN (37%) or public television/new [media] (37%).\nThe researchers further claimed that:\n:Since media coverage of Muslims and Islam is likely to shape the opinions of those who have limited or no contact with this religion and its people, it is important to analyze the potential associations these media portrayals might have with people's attitudes toward Islam in general and Muslims in particular.\n\n===Europe===\nA 2012 study indicates that Muslims across different European countries, such as France, Germany and the United Kingdom, experience the highest degree of Islamophobia in the media.<ref name=kunst2012b>{{cite journal | last1 = Kunst | last2 = Sam | last3 = Ulleberg | year = 2013| title = Perceived islamophobia: Scale development and validation | doi = 10.1016/j.ijintrel.2012.11.001 | journal = International Journal of Intercultural Relations | volume =  37| issue = 2| pages =  225\u2013237| url = https://zenodo.org/record/812038}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, the [[European Network Against Racism|ENAR]] (European Network Against Racism) conducted research and found that Muslim women are often portrayed as a suppressed group by the media. According to the reports, wearing a hijab, or any religious clothing is depicted as a form of the violation of women\u2019s rights by news agencies which puts Islam as a religion under a negative light.<ref name=\":0\">\u201cForgotten Women: The Impact of Islamophobia on Muslim Women .\u201d Forgotten Women: The Impact of Islamophobia on Muslim Women . European network against racism . Accessed November 6, 2019. <nowiki>https://www.enar-eu.org/IMG/pdf/factsheet9-european_lr_1_.pdf</nowiki>.</ref> Through social media platforms such as Facebook and Twitter, Muslim women are often targets of abuse, sexist insults and hate speeches. According to the reports, in 2015, 90% of the victims of Islamophobic incidents in Netherlands that were reported to Meld Islamophobia were Muslim women.<ref name=\":0\" /> The report also mentions that 64% of the British public receives information about Islam through mass media which may explain why the public displays feelings of hostility towards the Muslim Community, particularly the women.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAccording to the \"European Islamophobia Report 2018,\" released by the Foundation for Political, Economic and Social Research ([https://www.setav.org/en/ SETA]) in the [[Anadolu Agency]] newsletter, news media coverage in Europe, have minimal news that favour Muslim Groups.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/turkey/anti-muslim-racism-in-europe-on-rise-in-2018-report/1597957|title=Anti-Muslim racism in Europe on rise in 2018: Report|website=www.aa.com.tr|access-date=2019-11-08}}</ref> According to research carried out by the City University in London, only 0.5% of journalists in the UK are Muslim, and thus the underrepresentation of Muslim Journalists could be a crucial reason behind the lack of positive news coverage with regards to Muslim Communities.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/voices/why-the-british-media-is-responsible-for-the-rise-in-islamophobia-in-britain-a6967546.html|title=Why the British media is responsible for the rise in Islamophobia in Britain|date=2016-04-04|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-11-08}}</ref> Moreover, the report also mentioned that the Islamophobic language used in hate speeches by politicians could also impact the representation of Muslims in the minds of the Europeans.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nAn article by Jan Kovar in the UNYP Newsletter (University of New York in Prague), states that during the course of the migration crisis in Europe (2013-2016), Muslim migrants were portrayed as a security threat to the country in 77% and 67% of news stories by agencies in Czech and Slovak respectively, due to which their community experienced antagonism.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unyp.cz/news/islamophobia-europe-media-blame|title=Islamophobia in Europe: is the media to blame?|date=2018-11-27|website=University of New York in Prague|language=en|access-date=2019-11-08}}</ref>\n\nMiqdaad Versi of \u2018[[The Independent]]\u2019 filed a complaint when the \u2018[[Daily Star (United Kingdom)|Daily Star]]\u2019, published a headline stating, \u201cUK mosques fundraising for terror\u201d as it was misleading for the public. Following this, the newspaper clarified its error claiming that the UK mosques were actually \u201cnot involved in any way\u201d.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n===United Kingdom===\nIn 2008, [[Peter Oborne]] of ''[[The Independent]]'' wrote that British tabloids such as [[The Sun (United Kingdom)|''The Sun'']] tend to highlight crimes committed by Muslims in an undue and disproportionate manner.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/the-shameful-islamophobia-at-the-heart-of-britains-press-861096.html|title=The shameful Islamophobia at the heart of Britain's press|work=The Independent}}</ref> In 2013, British Muslim historian [[Humayun Ansari]] said that politicians and the media are still fuelling Islamophobia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/opinion/2013/07/201374135331488994.html|title=Islamophobia rises in British society|first=Humayun|last=Ansari|date=July 8, 2013|work=aljazeera.com}}</ref>\n\n[[John E. Richardson]]'s 2004 book ''(Mis)representing Islam: the racism and rhetoric of British broadsheet newspapers'', criticized the [[Media of the United Kingdom|British media]] for propagating negative [[Stereotypes of Arabs and Muslims|stereotypes of Muslims]] and fueling anti-Muslim prejudice.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Richardson|first=John E.|title=(Mis)representing Islam: the racism and rhetoric of British broadsheet newspapers|publisher=[[John Benjamins Publishing Company]]|year=2004|isbn=90-272-2699-7|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WanqiF2XULsC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=}}</ref> In another study conducted by John E. Richardson, he found that 85% of mainstream newspaper articles treated Muslims as a [[Muslims in British media|homogeneous mass]] who were imagined as a threat to British society.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Richardson | first1 = J. E. | year = 2009 | title = 'Get Shot of the Lot of Them': Election Reporting of Muslims in British Newspapers | url = | journal = Patterns of Prejudice | volume = 43 | issue = 3\u20134| pages = 355\u2013377 | doi=10.1080/00313220903109276}}</ref>\n\n==Social media==\nAccording to ''The Social Network of Hate: Inside Facebook's Walls of Islamophobia'', by British academic Imran Awan, Awan himself had went through 100 different Facebook pages online in which he found \"494 specific instances of online hate speech directed against Muslim communities.\"<ref name=494HateSpeech>{{cite web|url=http://www.middleeasteye.net/columns/social-network-hate-inside-facebooks-walls-islamophobia-1723501542|title=The social network of hate: Inside Facebook's walls of Islamophobia|work= Middle East Eye|first1=Imran |last1=Awan |date=29 July 2016 }}</ref> The five most common forms of abuse were:\n#that Muslim women were a security threat (15%)<ref name=494HateSpeech/>\n#that Muslims should be deported (13%)<ref name=494HateSpeech/>\n#that Muslim were potential terrorists (12%)<ref name=494HateSpeech/>\n#that Muslims were at war with non-Muslims (11%)<ref name=494HateSpeech/>\n#that Muslims were rapists (9%)<ref name=494HateSpeech/>\n\nIn 2016 in Europe, Facebook had created a new code of conduct that specified to decrease the hateful speech being used on the website.<ref name=\"European Commission\">{{cite web|url=http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_IP-16-1937_en.htm|title=European Commission - PRESS RELEASES - Press release - European Commission and IT Companies announce Code of Conduct on illegal online hate speech|website=europa.eu}}</ref> The head leader of public policy in Europe operating Twitter, Karen White, stated that \"Hateful conduct has no place on Twitter and we will continue to tackle this issue head on alongside our partners in industry and civil society. We remain committed to letting the tweets flow. However, there is a clear distinction between freedom of expression and conduct that incites violence and hate.\"<ref name=\"European Commission\"/>\n\n== Lack of representation ==\nSome have noted that few Muslims are represented in the media when discussing policies that affect Muslims directly. In 2017, journalists at ''Media Matters'' compiled a list of guests that were invited onto three US cable news shows ([[CNN]], [[Fox News]], [[MSNBC]]) in the week from January 30 to February 5 to discuss President Trump's controversial [[Executive Order 13769]], which would ban immigration from seven Muslim-majority countries. They found that of the 176 guests that were invited to discuss the issue, less than 8% were Muslim.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mediamatters.org/blog/2017/02/09/when-discussing-trumps-muslim-ban-cable-news-excluded-muslims/215284|title=When Discussing Trump's Muslim Ban, Cable News Excluded Muslims|last=Mast|first=Nina|date=9 February 2017|work=Media Matters for America|access-date=25 April 2017|last2=Alderman|first2=Julie}}</ref> In 2014, Palestinian activists noted a similar pattern with the underrepresentation of Palestinian guests on cable news during the [[2014 Israel\u2013Gaza conflict|2014 Israeli\u2013Gaza conflict]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/opinion/2014/08/why-are-palestinian-voices-exc-2014818111423499809.html|title=Why are Palestinian voices excluded?|last=Sabawi|first=Samah|date=21 August 2014|website=Al Jazeera English|access-date=25 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nA December 2015 survey by [[City, University of London]] of journalists found an underrepresentation of Muslims in the field in the UK. Only 0.4% of British journalists identified as Muslim or Hindu, 31.6% were Christian, and 61.1% had \"no religion.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/03/uk-poor-reporting-media-illiteracy-fuel-islamophobia-160329161759712.html|title=UK: Poor reporting, media illiteracy fuel Islamophobia|website=Al Jazeera English|access-date=2017-04-26}}</ref>\n\n== Disproportionate coverage ==\nIn 2009, [[Mehdi Hasan]] in the ''[[New Statesman]]'' criticized Western media for over-reporting a few [[Islamist terrorist]] incidents but under-reporting the much larger number of planned non-Islamist terrorist attacks carried out by \"non-Irish [[White people|white]] folks\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Know your enemy|author=Mehdi Hasan|work=[[New Statesman]]|date=9 July 2009|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/2009/07/mehdi-hasan-muslim-terrorism-white-british|accessdate=2010-04-09}}</ref>  A 2017 study by students at [[Georgia State University]] concluded that \"controlling for target type, fatalities, and being arrested, attacks by Muslim perpetrators received, on average, 449% more coverage than other attacks.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kearns|first=Erin M.|last2=Betus|first2=Allison|last3=Lemieux|first3=Anthony|date=5 March 2017|title=Why Do Some Terrorist Attacks Receive More Media Attention Than Others?|ssrn=2928138|journal=|volume=|pages=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Media personalities ==\nSome media personalities are associated with maintaining Islamophobic perspectives.\n\nThe obituary in ''[[The Guardian]]'' for the Italian journalist [[Oriana Fallaci]] described her as \"notorious for her Islamaphobia\" [sic].<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/italy/story/0,,1873911,00.html Obituary of Oriana Fallaci] \u2013 [[The Guardian]], 16 September 2006. \"''Controversial Italian journalist famed for her interviews and war reports but notorious for her Islamaphobia''\"</ref>\n\n== Arabophobia ==\nAfter the [[September 11 attacks|events of September 11]], coordinated by the [[Islamic terrorist]] organization [[Al-Qaeda]], the media's interest in Islam and the Muslim community has been significant but considered deeply problematic by some. Within minutes of planes crashing into the Twin Towers in New York, \"Muslim\" and \"terrorism\" had become inseparable. Many scholars{{Which|date=November 2019}} felt that the events of September 11 brought to the fore a marked tone of hysteria, frenzied and ill-informed reporting and a general decline in journalistic standards as far as discussions about Islam and Muslim were concerned.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite journal|last1=Ahmad|first1=Fauzia|title=British Muslim Perceptions and Opinions on News Coverage of September 11|journal=Journal of Ethnic and Migration Studies|date=August 2006|volume=32|issue=6|pages=961\u2013982|doi=10.1080/13691830600761479}}</ref>\n\nThe fear of Muslims has become more intensified ever since the attacks. The media portrays Islams as a race of people directly associated with violence. In public discussions and in the media, Muslims are mostly portrayed as a monolithic bloc, a closed and united group of people who are totally different from or even intimidating and hostile to a likewise closed \"West,\" which is Christian, secular, liberal, and democratic. The description of the Muslims and Western worlds as two contrasting and contradictory poles leads to a dualistic understanding of relations, disregarding many fine distinctions and exceptions. The so called risk of Arabs has been hyped throughout by the media channels to an extent that now Westerners see Muslims only in the context of somebody who is an adversary of the democratic world order and modernization.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\" />\n\n=== Arabophobia stats ===\nWhen Muslims and Islam are discussed on news networks, it is often regarding the \"[[War on Terror]].\"<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Pervez|first1=Sadia|title=Portrayal of Arabs and Islam in the talk shows of CNN & Fox News|journal=Journal of Media Studies|date=July 2010|volume=25|issue=2|pages=122\u2013140}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#ddd;\"\n| colspan=\"6\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''Depiction of Arabs on U.S. News channels'''\n|-\n! Issues !! Fox News !! Special Report !! Larry King Live !! Late Edition !! Total\n|-\n| Art & Culture || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| Crisis (Socio-eco) || 4 || 19 || 3 || 4 || 30\n|-\n| Development || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| Human Rights || 0 || 1 || 0 || 0 || 1\n|-\n| International Relations || 0 || 1 || 0 || 0 || 1\n|-\n| Religion || 0 || 3 || 2 || 0 || 5\n|-\n| Politics || 6 || 9 || 5 || 12 || 32\n|-\n| War on Terror || 13 || 10 || 14 || 13 || 50\n|-\n| Total || 23 || 43 || 24 || 29 || 119\n|}\n\n== Response ==\nSome media outlets are working explicitly against Islamophobia, and sometimes, the government is accused of conspiring.<ref>{{cite news|last1=German|first1=Lindsey|title='Blame the Muslims': Islamophobia is fuelled by government and media|url=http://www.middleeasteye.net/columns/blame-muslims-islamophobia-fuelled-government-and-media-877365179|agency=Middle East Eye|date=Feb 11, 2015}}</ref> In 2008, [[Fairness and Accuracy in Reporting]] (\"FAIR\") published a study \"Smearcasting, How Islamophobes Spread Bigotry, Fear and Misinformation.\" The report cites several instances where mainstream or close to mainstream journalists, authors, and academics have made analyses that essentialize negative traits as an inherent part of Muslims' moral makeup.<ref>Steve Rendall and Isabel Macdonald, [http://fair.org/extra-online-articles/making-islamophobia-mainstream/ Making Islamophobia Mainstream; How Muslim-bashers broadcast their bigotry], summary of [[Fairness and Accuracy in Reporting]] report, at its website, November/December 2008.</ref> FAIR also established the \"[[Forum Against Islamophobia and Racism]]\", designed to monitor coverage in the media and establish dialogue with media organizations. Following the [[September 11 attacks|attacks of September 11, 2001]], the [[Islamic Society of Britain]]'s \"Islam Awareness Week\" and the \"Best of British Islam Festival\" were introduced to improve community relations and raise awareness about Islam.<ref>Encyclopedia of Race and Ethnic studies, p. 218</ref> In 2012, the [[Organisation of Islamic Cooperation]] stated that they will launch a TV channel to counter  Islamophobia.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/411340 | title=OIC will launch channel to counter Islamophobia | date=April 19, 2012 | agency=Arab News | accessdate=January 9, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n== Pushback ==\nTwo days after completing his short book: ''Lettre aux escrocs de l'islamophobie qui font le jeu des racistes (Letter to the Islamophobia Frauds Who Play into the Hands of Racists)'', [[Charb|St\u00e9phane \"Charb\" Charbonnier]], editor of [[Charlie Hebdo]], was dead. Charb and 11 others were murdered on January 7, 2015 by [[Charlie Hebdo shooting#Ch\u00e9rif and Sa\u00efd Kouachi|Ch\u00e9rif and Said Kouachi]] in their [[Charlie Hebdo shooting|attack on the Parisian office]] of the satirical magazine.\n\nDuring his time as editor, Charlie Hebdo aimed its satire at Catholicism, Judaism and radical Islam in equal measure. In his final, posthumous missive, Charb rejects all accusations that he ran a \"racist\" or \"Islamophobic\" magazine. \"He argues\u2014from a left-wing, anti-racist, militantly secular viewpoint\u2014that the word \"Islamophobia\" is a trap, set by an unholy alliance of Muslim radicals and the unthinking, liberal Western media. The real issue, he says, is racism and Charlie Hebdo was never racist...\"<ref name=Independent>{{cite news|title=Charlie Hebdo editor's final book: 'Letter to the Islamophobia Frauds Who Play into the Hands of Racists'|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/charlie-hebdo-editors-final-book-letter-to-the-islamophobia-frauds-who-play-into-the-hands-of-racists-10193565.html|agency=The Independent (London)|publisher=Independent Digital News and Media Ltd.|date=April 22, 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:2011-11-02 Incendie \u00e0 Charlie Hebdo - Charb - 06.jpg|thumb|Charb on November 2, 2011]]\n:Really, the word \"Islamophobia\" is badly chosen if it's supposed to described the hatred which some lame-brains have for Muslims. And it is not only badly chosen, it is dangerous. From a purely etymological viewpoint, Islamophobia ought to mean \"fear of Islam\"\u2014yet the inventors, promoters and users of this word deploy it to denounce hatred of Muslims. But isn't it odd that \"Muslimophobia,\" or just \"racism,\" isn't used instead of \"Islamophobia.\"\n\n:...\n\n:Racist language\u2014which pressure groups, politicians and intellectuals had managed to corral in the space between the mouth of the xenophobe and his kitchen door\u2014has escaped into the street. It flows through the media and sullies the networks of social media.\n\n:So, yes, we are in the middle of an explosion of racist behavior\u2014yet the word \"racism\" is used only timidly, and is on the way to being supplanted by \"Islamophobia.\" And the campaigners for multiculturalism, who try to foist the notion of \"Islamophobia\" on the judicial and political authorities, have only one aim in mind: to force the victims of racism into identifying themselves as Muslims.\n\n:The fact that racists are also Islamophobic is, I'm afraid, irrelevant. They are, first and foremost, racists. By attacking Islam, they are targeting foreigners or people of foreign origin. But by focusing only on their Islamophobia, we are minimizing the danger of racism. The anti-racist campaigners of old are in danger of becoming overspecialized niche retailers in a minority form of discrimination.\n\n:...\n\n:However, why do the cartoonists of Charlie Hebdo, who know that their drawings will be exploited by the media, by the retailers of anti-Islamophobia, by far-right Muslims and nationalists, insist on drawing Mohamed and other \"sacred\" symbols of Islam? Simply because the Charlie Hebdo drawings do not have the vast majority of Muslims as their target. We believe that Muslims are capable of recognising a tongue-in-cheek.<ref name=Charb>{{cite book|last1=Charb|last2=Translated by John Lichfield|title=Lettre aux escrocs de l'islamophobie qui font le jeu des racistes (Letter to the Islamophobia Frauds Who Play into the Hands of Racists)|date=April 16, 2015|publisher=French and European Publications Inc.|location=France|isbn=978-2357660861|pages=1\u201396|edition=First}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Islamophobia]]\n** [[Islamophobia in Australia]]\n** [[Islamophobia in Canada]]\n** [[Islamophobia in Norway]]\n** [[Islamophobia in Sweden]]\n** [[Islamophobia in the United Kingdom]]\n** [[Islamophobia in the United States]]\n** [[Islamophobia in India]]\n** [[Islamophobia Watch]]\n* [[List of critics of Islam]]\n* [[Xenophobia]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Media bias]]\n[[Category:Islamophobia]]\n", "name_user": "Toddy1", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSocial media:s", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Islamophobia_in_the_media"}
{"title_page": "List of federal judges appointed by Woodrow Wilson", "text_new": "[[File:Ww28.jpg|thumb|right|Woodrow Wilson.]]\nFollowing is a list of all '''[[Article III of the United States Constitution|Article III]] [[United States federal judge]]s appointed by [[President of the United States|President]] [[Woodrow Wilson]]''' during his presidency.<ref>All information on the names, terms of service, and details of appointment of federal judges is derived from the [[Biographical Directory of Federal Judges]], a public-domain publication of the [[Federal Judicial Center]].</ref> In total Wilson appointed 75 Article III federal judges, including 3 Justices to the [[Supreme Court of the United States]], 20 judges to the [[United States Courts of Appeals]], and 52 judges to the [[United States district courts]].\n\nWilson made additional appointments to [[Article I of the United States Constitution|Article I]] tribunals.  He made 4 appointments to the [[United States Court of Customs Appeals]]. He also made 4 appointments to the [[Board of General Appraisers]], the forerunner of the [[United States Customs Court]] and later the [[United States Court of International Trade]].\n\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nFile:Brandeisl.jpg|Wilson appointed Louis Brandeis, the first Jewish Supreme Court justice.\nFile:James C. McReynolds - c1913.jpg|[[James Clark McReynolds]] was Wilson's first and longest-serving Supreme Court appointment.\n</gallery>\n\n==United States Supreme Court Justices==\n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n\n|-\n! #\n! Justice\n! [[List of Justices of the Supreme Court of the United States by seat|Seat]]\n! State\n! Former Justice\n! Nomination<br>date\n! Confirmation<br>date\n! Began<br>{{nowrap|active service}}\n! Ended<br>active service\n! Ended<br>{{nowrap|retired service}}\n\n|-\n| {{nts|1}}\n| {{nowrap|{{sortname|James Clark|McReynolds}}}}\n| align=\"center\" | {{sort|03|3}}\n| [[Tennessee]]\n| {{sortname|Horace Harmon|Lurton}}\n| {{dts|1914|08|19}}\n| {{dts|1914|08|29}}\n| {{dts|1914|08|29}}\n| {{dts|1941|01|31}}\n| {{dts|1946|08|24}}\n\n|-\n| {{nts|2}}\n| {{sortname|Louis|Brandeis}}\n| align=\"center\" | {{sort|04|4}}\n| [[Massachusetts]]\n| {{sortname|Joseph Rucker|Lamar}}\n| {{dts|1916|01|28}}\n| {{dts|1916|06|01}}\n| {{dts|1916|06|01}}\n| {{dts|1939|02|13}}\n| {{dts|1941|10|05}}\n\n|-\n| {{nts|3}}\n| {{sortname|John Hessin|Clarke}}\n| align=\"center\" | {{sort|06|6}}\n| [[Ohio]]\n| {{nowrap|{{sortname|Charles Evans|Hughes}}}}\n| {{dts|1916|07|14}}\n| {{dts|1916|07|24}}\n| {{dts|1916|07|24}}\n| {{dts|1922|09|18}}\n| align=\"center\" | {{sort|0|\u2013}}\n\n|}\n\n==Courts of Appeals==\n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n\n|- bgcolor=\"#ececec\"\n! #\n! Judge\n! Circuit\n! Nomination<br/>date\n! Confirmation<br/>date\n! Began active<br/>service\n! Ended active<br/>service\n! Ended senior<br/>status\n\n|-\n| {{nts|1}}\n| {{sortname|George Hutchins|Bingham}}\n| {{sort|01|[[United States Court of Appeals for the First Circuit|First]]}}\n| {{dts|1913|05|15}}\n| {{dts|1913|06|05}}\n| {{dts|1913|06|05}}\n| {{dts|1939|03|23}}\n| {{dts|1949|09|25}}\n\n|-\n| {{nts|2}}\n| {{sortname|Charles Albert|Woods}}\n| {{sort|04|[[United States Court of Appeals for the Fourth Circuit|Fourth]]}}\n| {{dts|1913|04|24}}\n| {{dts|1913|06|05}}\n| {{dts|1913|06|05}}\n| {{dts|1925|06|21}}\n| align=\"center\" |{{sort|0|\u2013}}\n\n|-\n| {{nts|3}}\n| {{sortname|Henry Wade|Rogers}}\n| {{sort|02|[[United States Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit|Second]]}}\n| {{dts|1913|09|18}}\n| {{dts|1913|09|29}}\n| {{dts|1913|09|29}}\n| {{dts|1926|08|16}}\n| align=\"center\" |{{sort|0|\u2013}}\n\n|-\n| {{nts|4}}\n| {{sortname|Victor Baynard|Woolley}}\n| {{sort|03|[[United States Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit|Third]]}}\n| {{dts|1914|08|07}}\n| {{dts|1914|08|12}}\n| {{dts|1914|08|12}}\n| {{dts|1938|05|01}}\n| {{dts|1945|02|22}}\n\n|-\n| {{nts|5}}\n| {{sortname|Richard Wilde|Walker Jr.}}\n| {{sort|05|[[United States Court of Appeals for the Fift